{"title_page": "Claudiu Teohari", "text_new": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Claudiu Teohari\n| image = [[File:Claudiu Teohari doing stand-up.jpg|200px]]\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Teo performing in 2013\n| alt = Teo\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Bucharest]], [[Romania]]\n| medium = {{flatlist|\n*[[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]]\n*\n*[[television]]\n*[[film]]\n}}\n| active = 2004\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n*[[Observational comedy]]\n*[[satire]]\n*[[black comedy]]\n*[[blue comedy]]\n*[[self-deprecation]]\n}}\n| subject = {{flatlist|\n*[[Everyday life]]\n*[[gender differences]]\n*[[human behavior]]\n*[[embarrassment|social awkwardness]]\n*[[human sexuality]]\n*[[racism]]\n*[[patriotism]]\n}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Melinda Kutasi Teohari|2015}}\n| children =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|https://www.facebook.com/teostandup}}\n}}\n'''Claudiu Mihail Teohari''' (born November 11, 1981), known professionally as Teo, is a Romanian stand up-comedian, writer and occasional actor. After rising to fame in his native Romania as a household name in [[Bucharest]]'s Deko Caf\u00e9, he was catapulted to Internet superstardom by a series of [[YouTube]] recordings of his routines that went viral. As an actor, he made a cameo appearance in Dan Chi\u0219u's 2010 directorial debut, WebSiteStory.<ref>{{cite news |last=Arvunescu|first=Victor |title= Statutul comediantului rom\u00e2n, \u00eentr-o discu\u0163ie liber\u0103 cu Raul Gheba \u015fi Teo: \"O s\u0103 devenim \u015fi noi destul de b\u0103tr\u00e2ni \u00eenc\u00e2t s\u0103 ne ducem pe TV \" |work=Comedy |publisher=[[Adev\u0103rul]] |date=March 14, 2016 |url=http://adevarul.ro/entertainment/tv/interviu-statutul-comediantului-roman-intr-o-discutie-libera-raul-gheba-teo-o-devenim-destul-batrani-ducem-tv--1_56e59f3b5ab6550cb8cf088c/index.html  |location=Bucharest|series=Entertainment/TV |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3901380/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1|title=Claudiu Teohari - IMDb|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"hotnews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-cultura-2094381-special-stand-comedy-trupa-deko.htm |title=SPECIAL de stand up comedy cu Trupa DeKO - Cultura |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref name=\"hotnews1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1150633-stand-comedy-cafe-deko.htm |title=Stand up comedy la Cafe DeKO - Arhiva noiembrie 2007 |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1156450-stand-comedy-trupa-deko.htm |title=STAND UP comedy cu Trupa DeKO - Arhiva noiembrie 2007 |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videonews.ro/video/romania/teo-la-noi-se-lucreaza-cu-toporul-pentru-ca-oriciul-e-foarte-gros.html |title=VideoNews :: Homepage |publisher=Videonews.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena3.ro/romania/dincolo-de-stiri-despre-comedie-politica-si-societate-cu-teo-si-bogdan-naumovici-242386.html |title=Dincolo de \u015etiri. Despre comedie, politic\u0103 \u015fi societate, cu Teo \u015fi Bogdan Naumovici |publisher=Antena3.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gandul.info/magazin/comediantul-teo-invitatul-lucian-mindruta-schimba-vorba-discursul-public-e-parerea-dreptul-parere-nimeni-obligatia-asculte-inteleg-simti-obligatia-emiti-11456369 |title=Comediantul Teo, invitatul lui Lucian M\u00eendru\u0163\u0103 la \"Schimb\u0103 vorba\": \"\u00cen discursul public, <> e p\u0103rerea. Ai dreptul la o p\u0103rere. Nu are nimeni obliga\u0163ia s\u0103 o asculte, \u015fi, ce nu \u00eenteleg eu, de ce simti tu obliga\u0163ia s\u0103 o emi\u0163i\" - Gandul |publisher=Gandul.info |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafax.ro/life-inedit/ventrilocul-jimmy-tamley-in-premiera-in-romania-la-gala-premiilor-stand-up-comedy-din-bucuresti-10538447 |title=Ventrilocul Jimmy Tamley, \u00een premier\u0103 \u00een Rom\u00e2nia, la gala premiilor Stand Up Comedy din Bucure\u015fti - Mediafax |publisher=Mediafax.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/ploiesti/teo-deko-show-stand-up-comedy-back-door-ploiesti-1_50ae25eb7c42d5a6639a07ec/index.html |title=Teo de la Deko, show de stand-up comedy \u00een \"Back Door\" Ploie\u0219ti |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - IMPROVIZATIE @ CLUB99 - EPISODUL 1 |publisher=Voyo.ro |accessdate=2014-03-16 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421105702/http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |archivedate=2014-04-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/10033-improvizatie-club99-episodul-2 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - IMPROVIZATIE @ CLUB99 - EPISODUL 2 |publisher=Voyo.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Octombrie 29, 2013 |url=http://www.clujlife.com/2013/10/29/interviu-andrei-ciobanu/ |title=Interviu: Andrei Ciobanu - Evenimente din Cluj Napoca |publisher=Clujlife.com |date=2013-10-29 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/cluj-napoca/teo-vio-costel-politicieni-1_52811368c7b855ff56e3aaab/index.html |title=VIDEO Discu\u0163ii serioase cu Teo, Vio \u015fi Costel, cei mai buni comedian\u0163i din \u0163ar\u0103: \"Nu facem glume despre politicieni, pentru c\u0103 fac singuri mi\u015fto de ei\" |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informatia-zilei.ro/sm/teo-a-destins-atmosfera-la-club-poesis-in-doua-show-uri-incendiare/ |title=Teo a destins atmosfera la Club Poesis \u00een dou\u0103 show-uri incendiare &#124; Informa\u0163ia Zilei |publisher=Informatia-zilei.ro |date=2009-07-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mihaela Manole |url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/invitatie-in-meandrele-netului-855538.html |title=Invita\u0163ie \u00een meandrele netului > |publisher=EVZ.ro |date=2009-06-19 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/entertainment/celebritati/claudiu-teohari--blogosfera-romaneasca-e-continua-crestere-1_50ad057c7c42d5a6638da0d5/index.html |title=Claudiu Teohari : \"Blogosfera rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 e \u00een continu\u0103 cre\u015ftere\" |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Stefan Petre www.eyecon.ro |url=http://www.esquire.ro/articole/reportaje/un-tip-intra-intr-un-bar.htm |title=Un tip intr\u0103 \u00eentr-un bar - Esquire |publisher=Esquire.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metropotam.ro/La-zi/Teo-va-deschide-show-ul-lui-Pablo-Francisco-de-la-Bucuresti-art2975754042/ |title=Teo va deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti &#124; La zi pe Metropotam |publisher=Metropotam.ro |date=2013-10-30 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\nHe currently lives in [[Bucharest]] with his wife, former [[Playboy playmate]] Melinda Kutasi.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nClaudiu was born in [[Bucharest]] in 1981. The grandson of an airline pilot who occasionally flew Romanian dictator [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]]'s official plane, he grew up in the [[Bucharest]] neighborhood of Titan. While attending highschool, he played in a rock band, wrote articles for the school newspaper, and traveled Europe with the George Co\u0219buc Highschool [[debating|debate]] team. He has said that [[competitive debating]] had a great influence on the way he came to approach writing and stand-up later in his life.<ref name=\"kmkz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kmkz.ro/de-pe-teren/interviu-dezvaluiri/teo-curge-stand-up-prin-mine/ |title=Teo: \"Curge stand-up prin mine\" &#124; Revista Kamikaze |publisher=Kmkz.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> After graduating he attended the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]] where he studied business management. He has stated in interviews that he found it to be a waste of his time and regrets the time spent there.<ref name=\"outinmures1\">{{cite web|url=http://outinmures.ro/interviu-cu-teo-comediantul/ |title=Interviu cu Teo, comediantul Unde Iesim in Mures? |publisher=Outinmures.ro |date=2012-10-28 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTeo started considering doing stand-up in 2003, while working in retail.<ref name=\"Episode 8 of the weekly podcast Teohari is hosting, detailing his work before stand-up\">{{Cite episode |title=Episodul 8 - Hateri, Bivolaru si Amintiri din copilarie |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/intre-showuri-podcast/intre-showuri-cu-teo-vio-si-costel-episodul-8 |access-date=11 April 2016 |series=\u00centre Showuri |series-link= |first= |last= |network=[[SoundCloud]] |station= |date=6 April 2016 |season= |series-no= |number=8 |minutes=28:10 |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |language=Romanian}}</ref> His first public performance took place in early 2004 in Deko Caf\u00e9, a local comedy club in [[Bucharest]], during an [[open mic]] night. Prior to this experience, his only encounters with stand-up comedy had been [[Seinfeld]] and [[Robin Williams]]' Live on Broadway special, which he had seen at a friend's house and described his experience as transformative, in light of Williams' performance.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXkv8dDT3Ps</ref> He described his first gig on stage as unpleasant, his lack of experience being noticeable, but his enthusiasm won fellow stand-up comedian Mihai Bobonete's trust, and he was asked to come back for a few weeks before being invited to join the club's official roster as a featured performer.<ref name=\"kmkz\"/> Together with fellow comics Costel Bojog and Viorel Dragu, he became an overnight sensation when, in 2006, he published some of their routines on [[YouTube]]. A bit in which he deals with [[Romanian profanity]] and the way it reflects [[gender role]]s received national coverage and drew considerable attention to a phenomenon considered to be virtually unknown until then in Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bNoOusfqwMM |title=Teo - Cuvinte vulgare @Cafe Deko |publisher=YouTube |date=2006-12-29 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> He started touring extensively with Costel Bojog and Viorel Dragu and also got a job with [[Leo Burnett Worldwide]] as a copywriter which he quit when he was able to earn a steady income from stand-up.<ref name=\"iqool1\">{{cite web|url=http://iqool.ro/glorie-mielului-interviu-teo-club-99-nimic-nou/ |title=Interviu: Glorie lui Teo &#124; IQool |language=ro |publisher=Iqool.ro |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\nTeohari disassociated himself with Deko Caf\u00e9 and their brand in 2009 after a series of financial disagreements with the club's management.<ref name=\"kmkz\"/><ref name=\"outinmures1\"/> With Viorel Dragu and Costel Bojog, he founded Club 99, his own comedy club. He opened [[Pablo Francisco]]'s \"Live and Kickin'\" tour in [[Bucharest]] in front of a sold out [[Sala Palatului]], establishing himself as one of the most noteworthy comedy performers in Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kissfm.ro/hotonkiss/4353/Teo-deschide-show-ul-lui-Pablo-Francisco-de-la-Bucuresti.html |title=Teo deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti! &#124; Kiss FM &#124; Hot on Kiss |publisher=Kissfm.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myticket.ro/en/news/teo-va-deschide-show-ul-lui-pablo-francisco-de-la-bucuresti |title=Teo va deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti! &#124; News |publisher=Myticket.ro |date=2014-03-06 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iconcert.ro/pablo-francisco-sala-palatului-bucuresti.html |title=Pablo Francisco la Sala Palatului din Bucuresti |publisher=iConcert.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n\n===Dup\u0103 Bloguri===\n\nIn 2009, Teohari debuted his own weekly comedy show on [[Realitatea TV]] called ''Dup\u0103 Bloguri'', a pun on the [[Dup\u0103 blocuri]] album title by Romanian hip hop group [[B.U.G. Mafia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloguluteo.wordpress.com/2009/04/06/dupa-bloguri-si-bacau/ |title=\"Dupa Bloguri\" si Bacau &#124; BloguLuTeo |publisher=Bloguluteo.wordpress.com |date=2009-04-06 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Monica Cismaru |url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/dupa-bloguri-este-teo-847057.html |title=\"Dup\u0103 bloguri\" este Teo > |publisher=EVZ.ro |date=2009-04-12 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>http://www.evz.ro/divertisment-dupa-bloguri-video-846241.html</ref> The program examined various aspects of Romanian contemporary culture by focusing on weekly Internet stories about Romanian bloggers and writers. Together with producer Ana Maria Caia, he executive produced the weekly program until its cancellation in late 2009 after 20 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/claudiu-teohari-din-trupa-deko-va-prezenta-dupa-bloguri-la-realitatea-tv_491876.html |title=Claudiu Teohari, din trupa Deko, va prezenta Dup\u0103 bloguri, la Realitatea TV |publisher=Realitatea.net |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/teo-prezentatorul-emisiunii-dupa-bloguri-de-la-realitatea-tv-le-raspunde-fanilor-pe-tpu-ro_508177.html |title=Teo, prezentatorul emisiunii \"Dup\u0103 Bloguri\" de la Realitatea TV, le r\u0103spunde fanilor pe TPU.ro |publisher=Realitatea.net |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> Realitatea TV was consequently sued by Indie Studio, the show's production company, for refusing to pay a part of the production costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-media_publicitate-7267679-ancheteonline-inca-patru-firme-cer-falimentul-realitatea-media-catavencu.htm |title=AncheteOnline: Inca patru firme cer falimentul Realitatea Media SA si Catavencu SA - Media & Publicitate - HotNews.ro |publisher=Economie.hotnews.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Antena 2 controversy===\n\nIn 2011 Teohari appeared as a guest on the [[Antena 2 (Romania)|Antena 2]] [[tabloid talk show]] \"It's Showtime!\" and sparked controversy after bashing the show's format and stating that tabloid journalists are being intentionally harmful to their audiences. He talked about the experience on his personal blog, saying that he had been banned from appearing on the program again by the show's producers after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloguluteo.wordpress.com/2011/02/09/cum-a-fost-la-tv/ |title=Cum a fost la TV &#124; BloguLuTeo |publisher=Bloguluteo.wordpress.com |date=2011-02-09 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Nimic Nou==\n\nIn late 2013, Teo started hosting ''Nimic Nou'' (Nothing New), a [[YouTube]] series created by comedy writers Raul Gheba and Radu Alexandru.<ref name=\"iqool1\"/> Produced by Sector 7 as a biannual video blog that parodies Romanian viral videos, the show has become very successful in [[Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aVbFCmnCAq4 |title=Nimic Nou Episodul 1 |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/nimicnoucuteo |title=Nimic nou |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''WebSiteStory''\n| Stand up comedian<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Role''\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Dup\u0103 Bloguri''\n| Himself (host)\n|}\n\n===Internet===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\u2013present\n|''Nimic Nou''\n| Himself (host)\n|\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n|''\u00centre Showuri''\n| Himself (co-host)\n| Podcast \n|-\n|2018\u2013present \n| Cine\u0218tieCe \n| Himself (co-host) \n| Podcast \n|}\n\n====Stand-up specials====\nIn 2013, Teohari teamed up with [[Media Pro]] to release his first stand-up special on the video-on-demand service Voyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - STAND UP COMEDY @ CLUB 99 |publisher=Voyo.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> In 2015 and 2016 respectively, he appeared in two other half-hour specials on [[Comedy Central Extra]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cerban|first=M\u0103d\u0103lina |title=Comedy Central Extra a produs primul s\u0103u show \u00een Rom\u00e2nia. C\u00e2nd va fi difuzat |work=Magazin |publisher=[[G\u00e2ndul]] |date=15 December 2014 |url= http://www.gandul.info/magazin/comedy-central-extra-a-produs-primul-sau-show-in-romania-cand-va-fi-difuzat-13721782  |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Simionescu|first=Anca |title=Stand-up din Rom\u00e2nia, pe Comedy Central |work=\u0218tiri Media |publisher=[[Evenimentul Zilei]] |date=10 March 2016 |url= http://www.evz.ro/stand-up-din-romania-pe-comedy-central.html  |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> In 2017, Teohari released his first solo full-length special as a free streaming video on YouTube.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/teostandup/videos/10212425682700493/</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Stand Up Comedy @ Club99''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Stand Up Night''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Comedy Club''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Aprostcalipsa''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Afar\u0103 sunt ur\u0219i''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''AIA E!''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''100% P\u0103reri''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3901380}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teohari, Claudiu}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian comedians]]\n[[Category:People from Bucharest]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Claudiu Teohari\n| image = [[File:Claudiu Teohari doing stand-up.jpg|200px]]\n| imagesize = 200px\n| caption = Teo performing in 2013\n| alt = Teo\n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1981|11|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Bucharest]], [[Romania]]\n| medium = {{flatlist|\n*[[Stand-up comedy|Stand-up]]\n*\n*[[television]]\n*[[film]]\n}}\n| active = 2004\u2013present\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n*[[Observational comedy]]\n*[[satire]]\n*[[black comedy]]\n*[[blue comedy]]\n*[[self-deprecation]]\n}}\n| subject = {{flatlist|\n*[[Everyday life]]\n*[[gender differences]]\n*[[human behavior]]\n*[[embarrassment|social awkwardness]]\n*[[human sexuality]]\n*[[racism]]\n*[[patriotism]]\n}}\n| spouse = {{marriage|Melinda Kutasi Teohari|2015}}\n| children =\n| signature =\n| website = {{URL|https://www.facebook.com/teostandup}}\n}}\n'''Claudiu Mihail Teohari''' (born November 11, 1981), known professionally as Teo, is a Romanian stand up-comedian, writer and occasional actor. After rising to fame in his native Romania as a household name in [[Bucharest]]'s Deko Caf\u00e9, he was catapulted to Internet superstardom by a series of [[YouTube]] recordings of his routines that went viral. As an actor, he made a cameo appearance in Dan Chi\u0219u's 2010 directorial debut, WebSiteStory.<ref>{{cite news |last=Arvunescu|first=Victor |title= Statutul comediantului rom\u00e2n, \u00eentr-o discu\u0163ie liber\u0103 cu Raul Gheba \u015fi Teo: \"O s\u0103 devenim \u015fi noi destul de b\u0103tr\u00e2ni \u00eenc\u00e2t s\u0103 ne ducem pe TV \" |work=Comedy |publisher=[[Adev\u0103rul]] |date=March 14, 2016 |url=http://adevarul.ro/entertainment/tv/interviu-statutul-comediantului-roman-intr-o-discutie-libera-raul-gheba-teo-o-devenim-destul-batrani-ducem-tv--1_56e59f3b5ab6550cb8cf088c/index.html  |location=Bucharest|series=Entertainment/TV |accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"imdb\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm3901380/?ref_=fn_al_nm_1|title=Claudiu Teohari - IMDb|publisher=imdb.com|accessdate=2014-03-19}}</ref><ref name=\"hotnews1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-cultura-2094381-special-stand-comedy-trupa-deko.htm |title=SPECIAL de stand up comedy cu Trupa DeKO - Cultura |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref name=\"hotnews1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1150633-stand-comedy-cafe-deko.htm |title=Stand up comedy la Cafe DeKO - Arhiva noiembrie 2007 |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-arhiva-1156450-stand-comedy-trupa-deko.htm |title=STAND UP comedy cu Trupa DeKO - Arhiva noiembrie 2007 |publisher=HotNews.ro |date=2009-09-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videonews.ro/video/romania/teo-la-noi-se-lucreaza-cu-toporul-pentru-ca-oriciul-e-foarte-gros.html |title=VideoNews :: Homepage |publisher=Videonews.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.antena3.ro/romania/dincolo-de-stiri-despre-comedie-politica-si-societate-cu-teo-si-bogdan-naumovici-242386.html |title=Dincolo de \u015etiri. Despre comedie, politic\u0103 \u015fi societate, cu Teo \u015fi Bogdan Naumovici |publisher=Antena3.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gandul.info/magazin/comediantul-teo-invitatul-lucian-mindruta-schimba-vorba-discursul-public-e-parerea-dreptul-parere-nimeni-obligatia-asculte-inteleg-simti-obligatia-emiti-11456369 |title=Comediantul Teo, invitatul lui Lucian M\u00eendru\u0163\u0103 la \"Schimb\u0103 vorba\": \"\u00cen discursul public, <> e p\u0103rerea. Ai dreptul la o p\u0103rere. Nu are nimeni obliga\u0163ia s\u0103 o asculte, \u015fi, ce nu \u00eenteleg eu, de ce simti tu obliga\u0163ia s\u0103 o emi\u0163i\" - Gandul |publisher=Gandul.info |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediafax.ro/life-inedit/ventrilocul-jimmy-tamley-in-premiera-in-romania-la-gala-premiilor-stand-up-comedy-din-bucuresti-10538447 |title=Ventrilocul Jimmy Tamley, \u00een premier\u0103 \u00een Rom\u00e2nia, la gala premiilor Stand Up Comedy din Bucure\u015fti - Mediafax |publisher=Mediafax.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/locale/ploiesti/teo-deko-show-stand-up-comedy-back-door-ploiesti-1_50ae25eb7c42d5a6639a07ec/index.html |title=Teo de la Deko, show de stand-up comedy \u00een \"Back Door\" Ploie\u0219ti |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - IMPROVIZATIE @ CLUB99 - EPISODUL 1 |publisher=Voyo.ro |accessdate=2014-03-16 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140421105702/http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |archivedate=2014-04-21 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/10033-improvizatie-club99-episodul-2 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - IMPROVIZATIE @ CLUB99 - EPISODUL 2 |publisher=Voyo.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Octombrie 29, 2013 |url=http://www.clujlife.com/2013/10/29/interviu-andrei-ciobanu/ |title=Interviu: Andrei Ciobanu - Evenimente din Cluj Napoca |publisher=Clujlife.com |date=2013-10-29 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://adevarul.ro/locale/cluj-napoca/teo-vio-costel-politicieni-1_52811368c7b855ff56e3aaab/index.html |title=VIDEO Discu\u0163ii serioase cu Teo, Vio \u015fi Costel, cei mai buni comedian\u0163i din \u0163ar\u0103: \"Nu facem glume despre politicieni, pentru c\u0103 fac singuri mi\u015fto de ei\" |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.informatia-zilei.ro/sm/teo-a-destins-atmosfera-la-club-poesis-in-doua-show-uri-incendiare/ |title=Teo a destins atmosfera la Club Poesis \u00een dou\u0103 show-uri incendiare &#124; Informa\u0163ia Zilei |publisher=Informatia-zilei.ro |date=2009-07-07 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mihaela Manole |url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/invitatie-in-meandrele-netului-855538.html |title=Invita\u0163ie \u00een meandrele netului > |publisher=EVZ.ro |date=2009-06-19 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://adevarul.ro/entertainment/celebritati/claudiu-teohari--blogosfera-romaneasca-e-continua-crestere-1_50ad057c7c42d5a6638da0d5/index.html |title=Claudiu Teohari : \"Blogosfera rom\u00e2neasc\u0103 e \u00een continu\u0103 cre\u015ftere\" |publisher=adevarul.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Stefan Petre www.eyecon.ro |url=http://www.esquire.ro/articole/reportaje/un-tip-intra-intr-un-bar.htm |title=Un tip intr\u0103 \u00eentr-un bar - Esquire |publisher=Esquire.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metropotam.ro/La-zi/Teo-va-deschide-show-ul-lui-Pablo-Francisco-de-la-Bucuresti-art2975754042/ |title=Teo va deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti &#124; La zi pe Metropotam |publisher=Metropotam.ro |date=2013-10-30 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\nHe currently lives in [[Bucharest]] with his wife, former [[Playboy playmate]] Melinda Kutasi.\n\n==Early life and education==\n\nClaudiu was born in [[Bucharest]] in 1981. The grandson of an airline pilot who occasionally flew Romanian dictator [[Nicolae Ceau\u0219escu]]'s official plane, he grew up in the [[Bucharest]] neighborhood of Titan. While attending highschool, he played in a rock band, wrote articles for the school newspaper, and traveled Europe with the George Co\u0219buc Highschool [[debating|debate]] team. He has said that [[competitive debating]] had a great influence on the way he came to approach writing and stand-up later in his life.<ref name=\"kmkz\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kmkz.ro/de-pe-teren/interviu-dezvaluiri/teo-curge-stand-up-prin-mine/ |title=Teo: \"Curge stand-up prin mine\" &#124; Revista Kamikaze |publisher=Kmkz.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> After graduating he attended the [[Bucharest Academy of Economic Studies]] where he studied business management. He has stated in interviews that he found it to be a waste of his time and regrets the time spent there.<ref name=\"outinmures1\">{{cite web|url=http://outinmures.ro/interviu-cu-teo-comediantul/ |title=Interviu cu Teo, comediantul Unde Iesim in Mures? |publisher=Outinmures.ro |date=2012-10-28 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nTeo started considering doing stand-up in 2003, while working in retail.<ref name=\"Episode 8 of the weekly podcast Teohari is hosting, detailing his work before stand-up\">{{Cite episode |title=Episodul 8 - Hateri, Bivolaru si Amintiri din copilarie |episode-link= |url=https://soundcloud.com/intre-showuri-podcast/intre-showuri-cu-teo-vio-si-costel-episodul-8 |access-date=11 April 2016 |series=\u00centre Showuri |series-link= |first= |last= |network=[[SoundCloud]] |station= |date=6 April 2016 |season= |series-no= |number=8 |minutes=28:10 |time= |transcript= |transcript-url= |language=Romanian}}</ref> His first public performance took place in early 2004 in Deko Caf\u00e9, a local comedy club in [[Bucharest]], during an [[open mic]] night. Prior to this experience, his only encounters with stand-up comedy had been [[Seinfeld]] and [[Robin Williams]]' Live on Broadway special, which he had seen at a friend's house and described his experience as transformative, in light of Williams' performance.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wXkv8dDT3Ps</ref> He described his first gig on stage as unpleasant, his lack of experience being noticeable, but his enthusiasm won fellow stand-up comedian Mihai Bobonete's trust, and he was asked to come back for a few weeks before being invited to join the club's official roster as a featured performer.<ref name=\"kmkz\"/> Together with fellow comics Costel Bojog and Viorel Dragu, he became an overnight sensation when, in 2006, he published some of their routines on [[YouTube]]. A bit in which he deals with [[Romanian profanity]] and the way it reflects [[gender role]]s received national coverage and drew considerable attention to a phenomenon considered to be virtually unknown until then in Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=bNoOusfqwMM |title=Teo - Cuvinte vulgare @Cafe Deko |publisher=YouTube |date=2006-12-29 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> He started touring extensively with Costel Bojog and Viorel Dragu and also got a job with [[Leo Burnett Worldwide]] as a copywriter which he quit when he was able to earn a steady income from stand-up.<ref name=\"iqool1\">{{cite web|url=http://iqool.ro/glorie-mielului-interviu-teo-club-99-nimic-nou/ |title=Interviu: Glorie lui Teo &#124; IQool |language=ro |publisher=Iqool.ro |date=2014-03-12 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\nTeohari disassociated himself with Deko Caf\u00e9 and their brand in 2009 after a series of financial disagreements with the club's management.<ref name=\"kmkz\"/><ref name=\"outinmures1\"/> With Viorel Dragu and Costel Bojog, he founded Club 99, his own comedy club. He opened [[Pablo Francisco]]'s \"Live and Kickin'\" tour in [[Bucharest]] in front of a sold out [[Sala Palatului]], establishing himself as one of the most noteworthy comedy performers in Romania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kissfm.ro/hotonkiss/4353/Teo-deschide-show-ul-lui-Pablo-Francisco-de-la-Bucuresti.html |title=Teo deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti! &#124; Kiss FM &#124; Hot on Kiss |publisher=Kissfm.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.myticket.ro/en/news/teo-va-deschide-show-ul-lui-pablo-francisco-de-la-bucuresti |title=Teo va deschide show-ul lui Pablo Francisco de la Bucuresti! &#124; News |publisher=Myticket.ro |date=2014-03-06 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iconcert.ro/pablo-francisco-sala-palatului-bucuresti.html |title=Pablo Francisco la Sala Palatului din Bucuresti |publisher=iConcert.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Television==\n\n===Dup\u0103 Bloguri===\n\nIn 2009, Teohari debuted his own weekly comedy show on [[Realitatea TV]] called ''Dup\u0103 Bloguri'', a pun on the [[Dup\u0103 blocuri]] album title by Romanian hip hop group [[B.U.G. Mafia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloguluteo.wordpress.com/2009/04/06/dupa-bloguri-si-bacau/ |title=\"Dupa Bloguri\" si Bacau &#124; BloguLuTeo |publisher=Bloguluteo.wordpress.com |date=2009-04-06 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Monica Cismaru |url=http://www.evz.ro/detalii/stiri/dupa-bloguri-este-teo-847057.html |title=\"Dup\u0103 bloguri\" este Teo > |publisher=EVZ.ro |date=2009-04-12 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>http://www.evz.ro/divertisment-dupa-bloguri-video-846241.html</ref> The program examined various aspects of Romanian contemporary culture by focusing on weekly Internet stories about Romanian bloggers and writers. Together with producer Ana Maria Caia, he executive produced the weekly program until its cancellation in late 2009 after 20 episodes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/claudiu-teohari-din-trupa-deko-va-prezenta-dupa-bloguri-la-realitatea-tv_491876.html |title=Claudiu Teohari, din trupa Deko, va prezenta Dup\u0103 bloguri, la Realitatea TV |publisher=Realitatea.net |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.realitatea.net/teo-prezentatorul-emisiunii-dupa-bloguri-de-la-realitatea-tv-le-raspunde-fanilor-pe-tpu-ro_508177.html |title=Teo, prezentatorul emisiunii \"Dup\u0103 Bloguri\" de la Realitatea TV, le r\u0103spunde fanilor pe TPU.ro |publisher=Realitatea.net |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> Realitatea TV was consequently sued by Indie Studio, the show's production company, for refusing to pay a part of the production costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://economie.hotnews.ro/stiri-media_publicitate-7267679-ancheteonline-inca-patru-firme-cer-falimentul-realitatea-media-catavencu.htm |title=AncheteOnline: Inca patru firme cer falimentul Realitatea Media SA si Catavencu SA - Media & Publicitate - HotNews.ro |publisher=Economie.hotnews.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n===Antena 2 controversy===\n\nIn 2011 Teohari appeared as a guest on the [[Antena 2 (Romania)|Antena 2]] [[tabloid talk show]] \"It's Showtime!\" and sparked controversy after bashing the show's format and stating that tabloid journalists are being intentionally harmful to their audiences. He talked about the experience on his personal blog, saying that he had been banned from appearing on the program again by the show's producers after the incident.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloguluteo.wordpress.com/2011/02/09/cum-a-fost-la-tv/ |title=Cum a fost la TV &#124; BloguLuTeo |publisher=Bloguluteo.wordpress.com |date=2011-02-09 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Nimic Nou==\n\nIn late 2013, Teo started hosting ''Nimic Nou'' (Nothing New), a [[YouTube]] series created by comedy writers Raul Gheba and Radu Alexandru.<ref name=\"iqool1\"/> Produced by Sector 7 as a biannual video blog that parodies Romanian viral videos, the show has become very successful in [[Romania]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aVbFCmnCAq4 |title=Nimic Nou Episodul 1 |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-06-25 |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/nimicnoucuteo |title=Nimic nou |publisher=Facebook |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''WebSiteStory''\n| Stand up comedian<ref name=\"imdb\"/>\n| Cameo appearance\n|-\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class = \"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! class = \"unsortable\" | Role''\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''Dup\u0103 Bloguri''\n| Himself (host)\n|}\n\n===Internet===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\u2013present\n|''Nimic Nou''\n| Himself (host)\n|\n|-\n| 2016\u2013present\n|''\u00centre Showuri''\n| Himself (co-host)\n| Podcast \n|-\n|2018\u2013present \n| Cine\u0218tieCe \n| Himself (co-host) \n| Podcast \n|}\n\n====Stand-up specials====\nIn 2013, Teohari teamed up with [[Media Pro]] to release his first stand-up special on the video-on-demand service Voyo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voyo.ro/product/emisiuni/9963-stand-up-comedy-club-99 |title=Emisiuni - Let's Voyo! Vezi online cele mai tari filme, seriale si productii TV - VOYO.RO - STAND UP COMEDY @ CLUB 99 |publisher=Voyo.ro |date= |accessdate=2014-03-16}}</ref> In 2015 and 2016 respectively, he appeared in two other half-hour specials on [[Comedy Central Extra]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Cerban|first=M\u0103d\u0103lina |title=Comedy Central Extra a produs primul s\u0103u show \u00een Rom\u00e2nia. C\u00e2nd va fi difuzat |work=Magazin |publisher=[[G\u00e2ndul]] |date=15 December 2014 |url= http://www.gandul.info/magazin/comedy-central-extra-a-produs-primul-sau-show-in-romania-cand-va-fi-difuzat-13721782  |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Simionescu|first=Anca |title=Stand-up din Rom\u00e2nia, pe Comedy Central |work=\u0218tiri Media |publisher=[[Evenimentul Zilei]] |date=10 March 2016 |url= http://www.evz.ro/stand-up-din-romania-pe-comedy-central.html  |accessdate=10 April 2016}}</ref> In 2017, Teohari released his first solo full-length special as a free streaming video on YouTube.<ref>https://www.facebook.com/teostandup/videos/10212425682700493/</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+\n|-\n! Year\n! Album\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2013\n| ''Stand Up Comedy @ Club99''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2015\n| ''Stand Up Night''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''Comedy Club''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''Aprostcalipsa''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''Afar\u0103 sunt ur\u0219i''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''AIA E!''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n| 2020\n| ''100% P\u0103reri''\n| Performer\n| Stand up\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n*{{IMDb name|id=3901380}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Teohari, Claudiu}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Romanian comedians]]\n[[Category:People from Bucharest]]\n", "name_user": "Palexioan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed empty cells", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claudiu_Teohari"}
{"title_page": "Tazz", "text_new": "{{short description|American radio personality, color commentator and professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Taz<!-- MATCH ARTICLE TITLE -->\n|image       = Tazz 2.jpg\n|caption     = Tazz in 2008\n|birthname   = Peter Senercia<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|names       = Kid Krush<ref name=\"OwW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/t/tazz.html|title=Taz profile|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />The Tasmanian Devil<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />The Tazmaniac<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />'''Taz'''<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />Tazz<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|248|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|11}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|family      = [[Chris Chetti]] (cousin)\n|resides     = [[Long Island, New York]],<br>[[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|The Red Hook Section of Brooklyn, New York]]<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Johnny Rodz]]<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|debut       = {{start date|1987|6|3}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|retired     = {{end date|2002|4|1}}<ref name=Tazzvision/>\n}}\n'''Peter Senercia''' (born October 11, 1967),<ref name=\"slambio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/tazz.html|title=Taz bio|accessdate=July 20, 2007|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> better known by the [[ring name]] '''Taz''' (spelled '''Tazz''' in WWE) is an American [[radio host|radio personality]], [[color commentator]] and retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] currently signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW).\n\nHe is known for his work in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW), where he was a [[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|World Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwchampionship|title=ECW Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Television Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Television Championship|World Television Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtvtitlehistory|title=ECW TV Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|three time]] [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team Champion]],<ref name=\"ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ecw/ecw-t.html|title=ECW World Tag Team Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtaghistory|title=ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|two time (and the inaugural)]] [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"SolieFTW\" /> and the third (and final) ECW [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|Triple Crown Champion]].\n\nHis [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]] (WWF/E) career as an in-ring performer came to an early end in 2002 and subsequently saw him transition into a color-commentary role, which he continued to do until his contract with WWE expired in April 2009.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|title=Tazz's WWE Alumni Bio|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408030616/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|archivedate=April 8, 2009}}</ref> Two months later, Senerchia debuted in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] at their [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]] pay-per-view under his previous '''Taz''' ring name and eventually reprised his role as a color commentator for TNA's broadcasts, replacing [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]].\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Training, World Wrestling Council and independent circuit (1987\u20131993) ===\nSenerchia began wrestling in [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) and made his professional wrestling debut on June 3, 1987<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twnpnews.com/information/misc/debut.shtml|title=::Wrestler Debut Dates:: TWNP-Wrestling News and Information|first=Kevin|last=Romano|website=www.twnpnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwbts.com/features/debut.html|title=PWBTS 2000 - Your #1 News Source - \"As I See It\" - Bob Magee|first=Fritz|last=Capp|website=www.pwbts.com}}</ref> in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], after being trained by [[Johnny Rodz]]. He wrestled as Kid Krush before moving on to the [[Ring name|name]] The Tazmaniac, which he would use variations of for the rest of his career.<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In the early 1990s, as The Tazmaniac, he wrestled for [[International World Class Championship Wrestling]] (IWCCW) and held its [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship|Light Heavyweight Championship]] for six months in 1991.<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/icw/icw-lh.html|title=ICW/IWCCW Light Heavyweight Title|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref> He would follow [[Tony Rumble]] in leaving IWCCW to join the newly established [[Century Wrestling Alliance]] (CWA). He would also tour in [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW).\n\nWrestling as The Tasmaniac, Senerchia had his first [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) match on August 19, 1991, when he was defeated by [[Ray Odyssey]]. Appearing as The Tazmaniac, he then made his only appearance ever in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) when he defeated [[Joey Maggs]] in a dark match at a ''[[WCW Saturday Night|Saturday Night]]'' taping in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] on February 8, 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw93.htm |title=WCW 1993 |publisher=Thehistoryofwwe.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref> He would then make his second appearance in the WWF on May 5, 1993. Wrestling in a dark match at a Wrestling Challenge taping in Portland, ME, Tazmaniac would beat [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Taylor]]. He would go on to make two additional appearances on [[house show]]s in [[New Jersey]] on June 29 and June 30, losing to [[Jim Powers]] on each occasion.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm</ref>\n\n=== NWA Eastern / Extreme Championship Wrestling ===\n==== Early years and injury (1993\u20131995) ====\nIn October 1993, he and Joe Chetti (brother of [[Chris Chetti]]) debuted in the [[Philadelphia]]-based Eastern Championship Wrestling (ECW), prior to its name change to [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]], as the [[tag team]] The Tazmaniacs.<ref name=\"OwW\"/> When that team broke up, he was put into another team with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]], with whom he won the [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|Tag Team Championship]] twice.<ref name=\"ECWTT\"/><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/> During his second reign as Tag Team Champion with Sullivan, The Tazmaniac became a double champion when he also won the [[ECW World Television Championship|Television Championship]] for one night in March 1994.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> For most of the rest of the year he floated around the tag ranks, teaming with different partners. He held the title once more, this time with [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]], until Sabu was [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] fired by ECW owner [[Paul Heyman]] for [[No-show (professional wrestling)|no-showing]] an event in favor of touring Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\">{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW|Rise and Fall of ECW, The]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref> In August 1994, The Tazmaniac competed in a [[NWA World Title Tournament|one-night eight-man tournament]] for the vacant [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]], losing to [[Shane Douglas]] in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"Williams2013\">{{cite book|author=Scott E. Williams|title=Hardcore History: The Extremely Unauthorized Story of ECW|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EQtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|date=13 December 2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Company, Incorporated|isbn=978-1-61321-582-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref><ref name=\"Loverro2007\">{{cite book|author=Thom Loverro|title=The Rise & Fall of ECW: Extreme Championship Wrestling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0dlOLyCj6YC|date=22 May 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-6156-9|pages=67\u201378}}</ref>\n\nThe Tazmaniac was put out of action by a legit injury for much of 1995. On July 15, during a tag team match [[2 Cold Scorpio]] and [[Dean Malenko]] delivered a [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Aided piledriver|spike piledriver]] to him, and though he knew it was about to be performed, he did not have time to properly protect himself. As he explained on the DVD documentary ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]'', \"I landed right on my forehead and just jacked my whole neck back and that was it.\" The neck injury was so bad that, according to [[Tommy Dreamer]], hospital staff couldn't believe he'd walked into the hospital where he sought help after the match. Though he was unable to wrestle, Paul Heyman continued to pay him per their oral agreement, forging a loyalty between the men.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n==== Rise to superstardom (1995\u20131996) ====\nFollowing his neck injury, Taz made appearances with [[The Steiner Brothers]], even standing in their corner during matches with [[The Eliminators]] and getting physical with [[Jason Knight|Jason]]. It was at the [[November to Remember (1995)|November to Remember]] event, when Taz turned heel and joined up with referee [[Bill Alfonso]]. Working as the special referee for Alfonso's match with ECW commissioner [[Tod Gordon]], Taz refused to count to three and assaulted Gordon, then making the count for Alfonso. In his post-match promo, he claimed that no one was looking after him while he was injured and that no one cared (though Heyman was still paying him, the [[kayfabe]] story was that he had been forgotten and that Alfonso was the one helping him keep food on his family's table). He was also angry that Sabu was brought back in that very night.\n\nTaz returned to the ring on December 19, 1995 at Holiday Hell with a new look and wrestling style. The new character had him clad in a black/orange [[wiktionary:singlet|singlet]] and exhibiting a more physically intense in-ring style, focusing his offense on mat wrestling and [[suplex]]es (inspired by working with The Steiner Brothers), which announcer [[Joey Styles]] dubbed ''[[#In wrestling|Taz-Plexes]]'', earning him the nickname \"The Human Suplex Machine\". He also debuted his ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Half nelson choke|Tazmission]]''/Katahajime finishing maneuver, causing opponents to [[Submission (combat sport)|tap out]] to signal their submission as in [[mixed martial arts]] instead of nodding their head or vocally saying \"yes\". This quirk was soon picked up by other companies throughout the country.<ref>{{cite episode|title=12/17/95|series=History of ECW|network=[[WWE Classics On Demand]]| airdate=2007-08-14}}</ref> Heading into the summer, Taz began feuding with Tommy Dreamer, joining up with [[Brian Lee (wrestler)|Brian Lee]] to face Dreamer and [[Terry Gordy]] and later Dreamer and [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]]. Taz also developed a friendship with The Eliminators, based on mutual respect, and they occasionally involved themselves in his matches. [[Perry Saturn]] and Taz were both trainers at ECW's [[House of Hardcore]] wrestling school. For a while, some of the students, including Mako and [[Chris Chetti]], would accompany Taz and Alfonso to the ring as a faction known as Team Taz.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\nAt [[November to Remember (1996)|November to Remember]], things seemed to come full circle, as Taz stormed to the ring and interrupted Styles and \"stole Paul E.'s thunder\" by announcing that there would be a \"big show in the first quarter of the new year\", basically telling the fans in attendance that ECW's first [[pay-per-view]] was on the horizon. At that \"big show\", he guaranteed that Sabu would finally face him. Later that night, he came out to force Scorpio to leave the ring and went on an angry tirade, abusing Bob Artese and holding him hostage in the ring. Taz demanded Sabu come out and face him, and twice even led the crowd in a \"Sabu, Sabu\" chant to get him to enter the ring.  Several officials and wrestlers came out and Taz eventually got his hands on Paul E. The lights went out and when they came back on, Sabu was in the ring, across from Taz. This was the first time they had been in the ring together since early 1995. Before they could lock up, the lights went out again.\n\nDuring Sabu's match, where he teamed with [[Rob Van Dam]] to face The Eliminators and [[The Gangstas]] in a three-way dance, Taz attempted to attack his former partner, but Van Dam saved Sabu and was choked out in the aisle. This distraction caused Sabu to get hit with ''Total Elimination'' and his team lost. Taz also began a mini-feud with Rob Van Dam, dominating him in every match and was also out for a short time to get surgery on his injured shoulder. As 1996 ended and 1997 began, Taz and Sabu continued to try getting at one another, with no actual contact.\n\n==== World Television Champion (1997\u20131998) ====\nEarly in 1997, the antagonism between Sabu and Taz was growing, as Taz attacked Sabu's partner, Rob Van Dam, costing the team matches with The Eliminators and other teams. In the months leading to ECW's [[ECW Barely Legal|first pay-per-view]], Taz would choke out low-level wrestlers with the ''Tazmission'' due to viewing his matches as secondary to his rivalry with Sabu. He then dominated another series of matches with Van Dam before meeting Sabu at [[ECW Barely Legal|Barely Legal]], where Taz defeated him with the ''Tazmission'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1997b.html#041397|title=Barely Legal 1997 results| accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> only to have his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] [[Bill Alfonso]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turn]] on him and join Sabu and his partner [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In response, Taz began teaming with [[Chris Candido]] to face Sabu and Van Dam.\n\nTwo months later at [[Wrestlepalooza (1997)|Wrestlepalooza]], Taz lost to Sabu in the rematch, marking his first loss since 1995. However, later in the night, he won the World Television Championship from [[Shane Douglas]] to begin his second reign.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> He defended the title against all comers, including Douglas, [[Lance Storm]], [[John Kronus]], [[Al Snow]], [[Jerry Lynn]] and [[Chris Candido]]. Throughout late 1997, Taz began feuding with The Triple Threat in addition to Sabu and Van Dam, where he sometimes teamed up with [[Tommy Dreamer]] during the feud. At [[November to Remember (1997)|November to Remember]], he issued a challenge to World Heavyweight Champion Bam Bam Bigelow. The two would eventually meet, after Bigelow turned on Taz in a match against Shane Douglas and Chris Candido. Taz would ultimately lose the title to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] at [[Living Dangerously (1998)|Living Dangerously]] on March 1, 1998.\n\nAfter losing the World Television Championship, Taz was elevated into the World Heavyweight Championship picture. In May 1998, with Shane Douglas injured and unable to wrestle, Taz was given an old World Television Championship belt painted orange\u2014his trademark color\u2014and began [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|cutting promos]], declaring himself the [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]] at [[It Ain't Seinfeld]]. Though the championship was unsanctioned [[Kayfabe|in storyline]], it was defended at ECW shows until Douglas was healthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1998c.html#080298|title=Heat Wave 1998 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just before winning the World Heavyweight Championship, Taz \"gave\" the FTW Heavyweight Title to long-time foe Sabu in a match where he physically pulled Sabu on top of him to allow him to get the pin.<ref name=\"SolieFTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/ftwecw.html|title=Fuck The World title history|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\n==== World Heavyweight Champion and departure (1999) ====\nTaz finally defeated Shane Douglas for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[Guilty as Charged (1999)|Guilty as Charged]], thus ending Douglas' year-long reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999a.html#011099|title=Guilty as Charged 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz was supposed to defend the title against [[Chris Candido]] in his first televised title defense at [[House Party (1999)|House Party]] but Douglas attacked Candido before the match and took his place, whom Taz defeated to retain the title in his first successful title defense. He would then begin a feud with Sabu over Taz's World Heavyweight Championship and Sabu's FTW Heavyweight Championship. The rivalry culminated in a title unification match at the [[Living Dangerously (1999)|Living Dangerously]] pay-per-view, where Taz defeated Sabu to unify the FTW Heavyweight Championship into the World Heavyweight Championship. He would begin his next rivalry with Chris Candido, whom he defeated to retain the title at [[CyberSlam (1999)|CyberSlam]]. The two were scheduled to a rematch at [[Hardcore Heaven (1999)|Hardcore Heaven]], which Taz quickly won. However, he was attacked by [[Dudley Boyz]] after the match, leading to a title defense against [[Bubba Ray Dudley|Buh Buh Ray Dudley]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] in the main event later that night, which Taz won to retain the title. Taz then successfully defended the title against Candido on the June 4 episode of ''Hardcore TV'' to end the rivalry.\n\nTaz made his next successful title defense against [[Spike Dudley]] in a Falls Count Anywhere match on the June 25 episode of ''Hardcore TV''. He would begin feuding with the members of [[Steve Corino]]'s [[The Network (professional wrestling)|new rising stable]], primarily [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]. Taz successfully defended the World Heavyweight Championship against Tajiri at [[Hostile City Showdown (1999)|Hostile City Showdown]], the [[Heat Wave (1999)|Heat Wave]] pay-per-view and the September 3 episode of ''[[ECW on TNN]]''. During that time, Taz signed with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]], losing the title as the first man eliminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|three-way dance]] at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999c.html#091999|title=Anarchy Rulz 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher= Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> This ended his eight-month reign at 252 days. As he walked out of the ring, a large portion of the ECW locker room joined him on the entrance ramp to give him an emotional sendoff. After being off of ECW television for most of the fall, he wrestled one final match as an ECW performer at [[November to Remember (1999)|November to Remember]], losing to [[Rob Van Dam]] via [[Pin (wrestling)|pinfall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999d.html#110799|title=November to Remember 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz's final televised match in ECW aired on the November 13 episode of ''Hardcore TV'', in which he received a rematch against Mike Awesome for the World Heavyweight Championship, which he lost. In the DVD ''The Rise and Fall of ECW'', Taz said that he signed with the WWE because he was in the top of the company and he lost his passion.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2000-2009)===\n==== Hardcore Champion, feud with Jerry Lawler and The Alliance (2000\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nAfter being contacted by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) and [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021065026/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-10-21|title=Defection Inspection|last=Anderson|first=Steve|accessdate=July 17, 2008|date=October 2000|publisher=Wrestling Digest}}</ref> Taz debuted for the WWF, with the slightly modified ring name Tazz, at the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble]] with a win over the previously undefeated [[Kurt Angle]] at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble.html#00|title=Royal Rumble 2000 results|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just a few months after Tazz arrived in the WWF, [[Mike Awesome]], the man he had lost the ECW World Heavyweight Championship to at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]], secretly signed with WCW. Legal wrangling by Paul Heyman prevented Awesome from taking the championship belt with him, and in a bizarre piece of professional wrestling history, ECW and WWF officials agreed to have Tazz, a WWF wrestler, make a surprise appearance at an ECW show to defeat Awesome, a WCW wrestler, for the ECW World Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/02/19/3645984.html|title=Mike Awesome found dead|last= Oliver|first=Greg|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Sports]]}}</ref> Tazz held the title for ten days before losing it to [[Tommy Dreamer]], during which time he wore it on various WWF shows, including an episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' where he lost to the [[WWE Championship|WWF Champion]] [[Triple H]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |title=SmackDown! results \u2013 2000 |accessdate=July 23, 2007 |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |quote=April 20, 2000[...]WWF World Champion, Triple H, b ECW World Champion, Tazz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012210938/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref> However, [[Vince McMahon]] later expressed some regret over [[Professional wrestling booker|booking]] Tazz to lose to Triple H.<ref>{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the ECW World Heavyweight Championship, Tazz was placed into contention for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]], but never won the title. In the summer, after taking time off for an arm injury, he was turned into a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous character]] and placed into a feud with [[color commentator]] [[Jerry Lawler]].<ref name=\"slamint\"/> The feud included matches at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#2000|title=SummerSlam 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> and [[Unforgiven 2000|Unforgiven]], which they split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/unforgiven.html#2000|title=Unforgiven 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Tazz was only able to pick up the Unforgiven win when he received help from [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven]], who had returned to the company. Afterwards, the duo formed a [[tag team]] that lasted until November.\n\nWhen the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion]] angle began, Tazz acted as \"the voice of the [[The Alliance (professional wrestling)|WCW/ECW Alliance]]\", sticking up for them and speaking on their behalf whenever possible. He eventually left the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|stable]] after the leader [[Steve Austin|Stone Cold Steve Austin]] criticized his decision to stay on commentary rather than help ECW owner [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011108.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 8, 2001|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\n==== Commentator (2002\u20132009) ====\nWith injuries mounting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/01082008/articles/tazzshoots|title=Tazz shoots again|accessdate=January 11, 2008|author=Tazz|publisher=WWE|date=January 10, 2008}}</ref> Tazz began performing part-time commentary on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' in October 2000. He joined the ''SmackDown!'' team in February 2001 after Jerry Lawler quit the company, after calling his first [[pay-per-view]] on [[No Way Out (2001)|No Way Out]] with [[Jim Ross]], as well as becoming one of the trainers for the joint WWF/[[MTV]] produced reality series ''[[WWE Tough Enough|Tough Enough]]''.<ref name=\"slamint\">{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosT/tazz_01aug-can.html|title=Tazz talks: ECW, Tough Enough, WWF|last=Kapur|first=Bob |accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Wrestling]]}}</ref> Lawler returned to the company on November 19, 2001 and resumed his place as commentator, with Tazz becoming both a wrestler and a commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011122.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 22, 2001|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In January 2002, he and [[Spike Dudley]] won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael McAvennie|title=WWE The Yearbook: 2003 Edition|publisher=Pocket Books|year=2003|pages=13\u201316}}</ref> holding it for over a month before losing it to [[Billy and Chuck]].<ref name=\"WT-WWFTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwf/wwf-t.html|title=WWWF / WWF / WWE World Tag Team Title|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tazz.jpg|left|thumb|250x250px|Tazz signing autographs in 2006]]\nWhen World Wrestling Entertainment [[WWE Brand Extension|split into two brands]], Tazz was put on the [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] brand, where he resumed his color commentator duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 April 4, 2002|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917154817/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|archivedate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Not long after he retired from the ring, he became a full-time broadcaster.<ref name=Tazzvision>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2005/05/30/1063493.html|title=Tuning into Tazzvision|last=Zerr|first=Scott|accessdate =July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Wrestling]]}}</ref> He co-hosted ''SmackDown!'' for World Wrestling Entertainment until a third brand, [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]], was introduced in 2006, at which point he became the color commentator for that show.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/> He was also the co-host, with Joey Styles, of ''History of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'' on [[WWE 24/7 Classics]], a show that re-airs archived episodes of the original ECW's weekly television programs. Before and during episodes he and Styles provide insight into the storylines, inner workings, and general ambiance of ECW at the time\u2014as they remember it.\n\nIn February 2006, Tazz and his ''SmackDown!'' broadcasting partner, [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], hosted a week-long trial run of a show on [[Howard 100 and Howard 101|Howard 101]] on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], but the show was not picked up. He also hosted a talk show on [[WNYL (FM)|92.3 Free FM]] at sporadic intervals between late summer 2006 and early 2007, but it was not picked up and the station changed formats, replacing all post morning programming with music. On June 11, 2006, Tazz wrestled his final match to date, defeating Jerry Lawler at [[ECW One Night Stand (2006)|ECW One Night Stand]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ECW One Night Stand PPV Results 6/11/06 New York City, New York|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1150081251.shtml| publisher=WrestleView|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=June 11, 2006|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the recording of the April 29, 2008 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Tazz's broadcast partner [[Mike Adamle]] abruptly walked off set prior to the main event. Moments later, after reading the promo for the upcoming pay-per-view, Tazz walked out as well, leaving the main event with no commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2008/04/30/5428941.html|title=ECW: Announcing follies overshadow decent show|first=Matt|last=Bishop|accessdate=April 30, 2008|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Sports]]}}</ref> On December 13, 2010, Tazz joined Right After Wrestling and said that it \"pisses him off\" when companies try to re-create the original ECW. He stated that the original ECW worked because \"It was that era, that group of people, that leader in Paul Heyman. We were that little engine that could.\"<ref>[http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 Podcasts | The Score] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715182953/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 |date=2012-07-15 }}. Radio.thescore.com (December 13, 2010). Retrieved on 2011-11-29.</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Tazz filled in for [[Mick Foley]] as a color commentator on the SmackDown brand, while Raw wrestler [[Matt Striker]] filled in for Tazz on the ECW brand. When Foley left the company, Tazz became the permanent color commentator for the SmackDown brand once again. On April 3, 2009, Tazz left WWE when his contract expired. His WWE.com profile was moved from the active SmackDown roster list to the alumni list for a short time before being completely removed, confirming his departure from the company.\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2009\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Tazz and Mike Tenay.jpg|thumb|Taz (left) with his commentary partner, [[Mike Tenay]] in July 2010]]\nAt [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]], Senercia, under his Taz ring name, made his official [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) debut during [[Samoa Joe]]'s match against [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], revealing himself to be Joe's [[Kayfabe|on-screen]] adviser and consequently a [[heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] as well as an ally of the [[The Main Event Mafia|Main Event Mafia]]. The match ending was booked as Taz's presence enabling Joe to recover from Sting's ''[[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Scorpion Deathlock]]'' and win the match via submission after applying the ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Rear naked choke|Coquina Clutch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victory Road PPV Results \u2013 7/19/09|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1248058721.php|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=July 19, 2009|work=WrestleView|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the August 20, 2009 episode of ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', Taz replaced [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]] as the promotion's color commentator and also became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] upon stating that he was only loosely associated with the Mafia and that he had taught Joe everything he knew and that it was now up to Joe to use his newfound skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/font_color_770000_KELLER_S_TAKE_font_11/article_34814.shtml|title=Keller's TNA Impact report 8/20: Results, star ratings, thoughts, observations, quotebook|authorlink=Wade Keller|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=August 27, 2009|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impact: Blueprint gets the tables|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/08/21/10541866.html?cid=rsssportswrestling|last=Sokol|first=Bryan|author2=Sokol, Chris |date=August 21, 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> In May 2012, Taz began appearing as a judge in the monthly [[TNA Gut Check|Gut Check]] segment on ''Impact Wrestling''.<ref name=\"TNA3May\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_61084.shtml|title=Turner's TNA Impact Wrestling Results 5/3: Roode and RVD pick opponents for each other, Gut Check fall-out, Flair calls out Hogan|author=Turner, Scott|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=May 4, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref><!-- DO NOT ADD WEEK BY WEEK EVENTS, RUMORS OR SPECULATION. THIS INCLUDES ANNOUNCED MATCHES THAT HAVE NOT YET OCCURRED. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A NEWS SITE BUT AN ONLINE ENCYCLOPEDIA. Please see the articles \"Wikipedia:What Wikipedia is not\" and \"Wikipedia:Guide to writing better articles\" for more information. -->\n\nOn the January 17, 2013 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz was a [[groomsman]] at the wedding between [[Mark LoMonaco|Bully Ray]] and [[Brooke Hogan]]. As Ray and Brooke exchanged their vows, Taz interrupted the ceremony and proclaimed himself to be a member of [[Aces & Eights]] after revealing a [[kutte]] underneath his coat, turning heel again in the process. Following his revelation, Aces & Eights ambushed the ceremony and attacked Ray, his groomsmen [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Spike Dudley|Brother Runt]] and Brooke's father [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67961.shtml|title= KELLER'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/17: The Bully Ray-Brooke Hogan Wedding Episode \u2013 What happened? Did Hulk accompany Brooke? Did the wedding end without a hitch?|date=January 17, 2013|last=Keller|first=Wade|accessdate=January 17, 2013|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week on ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz revealed that he joined Aces & Eights because of his desire to be a member of a group that adheres to a higher power.<ref name=TazReason>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_68117.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/24: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Hardy vs. Daniels TNA Title match, Teflon Taz, wedding fall-out (updated w/Box Score)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Aces & Eights was forced to disband after Bully Ray lost to [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Anderson]], which also saw Anderson retain his career in TNA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_74692.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 11/21: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Turning Point\" Impact - TNA Title tournament continues, Bully vs. Anderson, more|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2015, it was  officially announced that Taz had departed TNA.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=JohnGaburick|author=John Gaburick|number=588450682002255873|date=15 April 2015|title=After 5+ years TNA &amp; Taz have mutually decided to part ways. A champ in the ring &amp; on the mic, we wish him nothing but success! @OfficialTAZ}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=OfficialTAZ|author=TAZ|number=588450023613988864|date=15 April 2015|title=Like to thank TNA Wrestling for the opportunity to apply my craft for past several years. Best wishes to them in the future.}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2016) ===\nIn November 2016, Tazz made an appearance on the [[WWE Network]] special, ''The Authentic Untold Story of ECW'', alongside former ECW management Paul Hayman and wrestlers Bubba Ray Dudley, D-Von Dudley, and Tommy Dreamer. In the one-hour special hosted by [[Corey Graves]], the guests talked about their experiences in ECW and the promotion's legacy on professional wrestling.\n\n=== All Elite Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn October 12, 2019, Taz made a guest appearance for [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), where he appeared on the October 22nd edition of ''[[AEW Dark]]'' as a guest commentator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/10/taz-to-guest-commentate-on-this-week-aew-dark-660674/|title=Taz To Guest Commentate On This Week's AEW Dark|publisher=Wrestling Inc.}}</ref> On November 9, 2019, Taz made his guest appearance during [[AEW Full Gear|Full Gear]] as the pre-show commentator. On the January 1, 2020 episode of ''[[AEW Dynamite]]'', Taz made his ''Dynamite'' debut on commentary filling in for [[Tony Schiavone]]. On January 16, 2020, it was announced that Taz had officially signed a multi-year deal with AEW, and he is set to be a member of the AEW broadcast team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescoops.com/taz-signs-multi-year-deal-with-aew/amp/|title=Taz Signs Multi-Year Deal With AEW|work=SEScoops.com|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling style and persona ==\nTazz's character was influenced by [[The Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]], [[The Steiner Brothers]] and [[Wild Samoans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-talks-early-disagreement-vince-mcmahon/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Talks About An Early Disagreement With Vince McMahon}}</ref> Tazz is nicknamed the \"Human Suplex Machine\" due to his wide array of suplex variations he would utilise in matches. His finishing move, the ''Tazmission'', is a half nelson choke with bodyscissors. He also sometimes combined this submission with a suplex, creating a half nelson choke suplex, called the ''Tazmission-Plex''.<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-coolest-maneuvers-of-all-time/page-16 |title=the 50 coolest maneuvers of all time|date=February 21, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014|publisher=WWE}}</ref> He has also claimed to have named the T-Bone Suplex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-says-named-t-bone-suplex/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Says He Named The T-Bone Suplex}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe has a [[tattoo]] of the [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Looney Tunes Tasmanian Devil]] on his upper right bicep accompanied by the legend Taz. His action figures produced by [[Jakks Pacific]] does not include the character, but does include the name. He has a self designed tattoo on his left lower bicep. Senerchia played [[Secondary school|high school]] [[high school football|football]]. Senerchia also studied [[judo]] prior to entering the professional wrestling circuit, reaching a second-degree black belt.<ref name=tazz73>Loverro, Thom (2006). ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]''. Pocket Books. {{ISBN|978-1-41-651312-4}}. p. 73</ref>  He is a fan of the [[New York Mets]], [[New York Knicks]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]], and the [[New York Jets]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==In other media==\nBeginning in 2018, Senercia was a nationally syndicated morning radio personality, co-hosting ''Taz and The Moose'' with Marc \"The Moose\" Malusis on [[CBS Sports Radio]] weekdays from 6-9 a.m. Eastern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbssports.radio.com/shows/taz-and-moose|title=Taz & The Moose - CBS Sports Radio}}</ref> In December 2019, Senercia announced he was leaving the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barrettsportsmedia.com/2019/12/17/taz-to-exit-cbs-sports-radio/|title=Taz To Exit CBS Sports Radio|date=2019-12-17|website=Barrett Sports Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>  \n\nSenercia also has his own podcast, called ''The Taz Show'', (formerly known as ''The Human Podcast Machine)'', where he discusses the latest in the professional wrestling world. The show has since discontinued. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.com/taz-show|title=The Taz Show|date=2018-04-30|website=RADIO.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nSenercia (as Tazz) appears as a playable character in ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007|SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]'' and ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009|SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n\n=== Amateur wrestling ===\n* Empire States Heavyweight Championship<ref>Noted by [[Joey Styles]] during the [[November to Remember 1997|1997 November to Remember]] broadcast</ref>\n\n=== Professional wrestling ===\n* '''[[Century Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n** [[CWA Cruiserweight Championship|CWA Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Cruiserweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"slambio\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/lhtcwa2.html|title=Solie's Title Histories: CWA - CENTURY WRESTLING ALLIANCE|website=www.solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern/Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=\"SolieFTW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Television Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/>\n** [[ECW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) \u2013 with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]] (2)<sup>1</sup> and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] (1)<ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/>\n** Third [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of ECW Triple Crown Champions|ECW Triple Crown Champion]]\n* '''[[International World Class Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\"/>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 10 of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1999.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1999|accessdate=November 24, 2015|publisher=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him No. 147 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the \"[[PWI Years]]\" in 2003\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|3 times]])<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/hardcore-championship|title=Hardcore Championship|website=WWE}}</ref>\n** [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Spike Dudley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|title=World Tag Team Championship \u2013 Tazz & Spike Dudley|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180601/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|archivedate=2012-10-24}}</ref>\n*'''''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Gimmick|Worst Gimmick]] (2013) <small>[[Aces & Eights]]</small><ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=35}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (2013)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=26}}</ref>\n*'''Victory Championship Wrestling'''\n**VCW Hall of Fame (Class of 2018)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Peter Senerchia|Tazz}}\n* {{IMDb name|name = Peter Senerchia}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name = Tazz}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131103092937/http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/1622-taz TNA profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{Aces & Eights}}\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taz}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Aces and Eights members]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LIU Post alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Alliance (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Dangerous Alliance members]]\n[[Category:The ECW Originals members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American radio personality, color commentator and retired professional wrestler}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestler\n|name        = Taz<!-- MATCH ARTICLE TITLE -->\n|image       = Tazz 2.jpg\n|caption     = Tazz in 2008\n|birthname   = Peter Senercia<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|names       = Kid Krush<ref name=\"OwW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/profiles/t/tazz.html|title=Taz profile|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref><br />The Tasmanian Devil<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />The Tazmaniac<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />'''Taz'''<ref name=\"OwW\"/><br />Tazz<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|height      = {{height|ft=5|in=9}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|weight      = {{convert|248|lb|kg|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1967|10|11}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|birth_place = [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]],<br>[[New York (state)|New York]], [[United States]]\n|family      = [[Chris Chetti]] (cousin)\n|resides     = [[Long Island, New York]],<br>[[United States]]\n|billed      = [[Red Hook, Brooklyn|The Red Hook Section of Brooklyn, New York]]<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/>\n|trainer     = [[Johnny Rodz]]<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|debut       = {{start date|1987|6|3}}<ref name=\"slambio\"/>\n|retired     = {{end date|2002|4|1}}<ref name=Tazzvision/>\n}}\n'''Peter Senercia''' (born October 11, 1967),<ref name=\"slambio\">{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/Bios/tazz.html|title=Taz bio|accessdate=July 20, 2007|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]}}</ref> better known by the [[ring name]] '''Taz''' (spelled '''Tazz''' in WWE) is an American [[radio host|radio personality]], [[color commentator]] and retired [[Professional wrestling|professional wrestler]] currently signed to [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW).\n\nHe is known for his work in [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]] (ECW), where he was a [[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship|World Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwchampionship|title=ECW Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Television Champions|two time]] [[ECW World Television Championship|World Television Champion]],<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtvtitlehistory|title=ECW TV Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|three time]] [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|World Tag Team Champion]],<ref name=\"ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/ecw/ecw-t.html|title=ECW World Tag Team Title|website=Wrestling-Titles.com}}</ref><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/ecwtaghistory|title=ECW Tag Team Championship|accessdate=December 2, 2013|work=[[WWE]]}}</ref> a [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|two time (and the inaugural)]] [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]],<ref name=\"SolieFTW\" /> and the third (and final) ECW [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)|Triple Crown Champion]].\n\nHis [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment]] (WWF/E) career as an in-ring performer came to an early end in 2002 and subsequently saw him transition into a color-commentary role, which he continued to do until his contract with WWE expired in April 2009.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|title=Tazz's WWE Alumni Bio|accessdate=August 23, 2008|publisher=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090408030616/http://www.wwe.com/superstars/wwealumni/tazz/bio/|archivedate=April 8, 2009}}</ref> Two months later, Senerchia debuted in [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] at their [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]] pay-per-view under his previous '''Taz''' ring name and eventually reprised his role as a color commentator for TNA's broadcasts, replacing [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]].\n\n== Professional wrestling career ==\n=== Training, World Wrestling Council and independent circuit (1987\u20131993) ===\nSenerchia began wrestling in [[World Wrestling Council]] (WWC) and made his professional wrestling debut on June 3, 1987<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.twnpnews.com/information/misc/debut.shtml|title=::Wrestler Debut Dates:: TWNP-Wrestling News and Information|first=Kevin|last=Romano|website=www.twnpnews.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwbts.com/features/debut.html|title=PWBTS 2000 - Your #1 News Source - \"As I See It\" - Bob Magee|first=Fritz|last=Capp|website=www.pwbts.com}}</ref> in [[San Juan, Puerto Rico]], after being trained by [[Johnny Rodz]]. He wrestled as Kid Krush before moving on to the [[Ring name|name]] The Tazmaniac, which he would use variations of for the rest of his career.<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In the early 1990s, as The Tazmaniac, he wrestled for [[International World Class Championship Wrestling]] (IWCCW) and held its [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship|Light Heavyweight Championship]] for six months in 1991.<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/us/newengland/icw/icw-lh.html|title=ICW/IWCCW Light Heavyweight Title|accessdate=July 21, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref> He would follow [[Tony Rumble]] in leaving IWCCW to join the newly established [[Century Wrestling Alliance]] (CWA). He would also tour in [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]] (NJPW).\n\nWrestling as The Tasmaniac, Senerchia had his first [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) match on August 19, 1991, when he was defeated by [[Ray Odyssey]]. Appearing as The Tazmaniac, he then made his only appearance ever in [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) when he defeated [[Joey Maggs]] in a dark match at a ''[[WCW Saturday Night|Saturday Night]]'' taping in [[Atlanta, Georgia]] on February 8, 1993.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/wcw93.htm |title=WCW 1993 |publisher=Thehistoryofwwe.com |date= |accessdate=2018-07-22}}</ref> He would then make his second appearance in the WWF on May 5, 1993. Wrestling in a dark match at a Wrestling Challenge taping in Portland, ME, Tazmaniac would beat [[Scotty 2 Hotty|Scott Taylor]]. He would go on to make two additional appearances on [[house show]]s in [[New Jersey]] on June 29 and June 30, losing to [[Jim Powers]] on each occasion.<ref>http://www.thehistoryofwwe.com/93.htm</ref>\n\n=== NWA Eastern / Extreme Championship Wrestling ===\n==== Early years and injury (1993\u20131995) ====\nIn October 1993, he and Joe Chetti (brother of [[Chris Chetti]]) debuted in the [[Philadelphia]]-based Eastern Championship Wrestling (ECW), prior to its name change to [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]], as the [[tag team]] The Tazmaniacs.<ref name=\"OwW\"/> When that team broke up, he was put into another team with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]], with whom he won the [[ECW World Tag Team Championship|Tag Team Championship]] twice.<ref name=\"ECWTT\"/><ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/> During his second reign as Tag Team Champion with Sullivan, The Tazmaniac became a double champion when he also won the [[ECW World Television Championship|Television Championship]] for one night in March 1994.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> For most of the rest of the year he floated around the tag ranks, teaming with different partners. He held the title once more, this time with [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]], until Sabu was [[Legit (professional wrestling)|legitimately]] fired by ECW owner [[Paul Heyman]] for [[No-show (professional wrestling)|no-showing]] an event in favor of touring Japan for [[New Japan Pro Wrestling]].<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\">{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW|Rise and Fall of ECW, The]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref> In August 1994, The Tazmaniac competed in a [[NWA World Title Tournament|one-night eight-man tournament]] for the vacant [[NWA World Heavyweight Championship]], losing to [[Shane Douglas]] in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"Williams2013\">{{cite book|author=Scott E. Williams|title=Hardcore History: The Extremely Unauthorized Story of ECW|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4EQtAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT56|date=13 December 2013|publisher=Skyhorse Publishing Company, Incorporated|isbn=978-1-61321-582-1|pages=56\u201357}}</ref><ref name=\"Loverro2007\">{{cite book|author=Thom Loverro|title=The Rise & Fall of ECW: Extreme Championship Wrestling|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j0dlOLyCj6YC|date=22 May 2007|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=978-1-4165-6156-9|pages=67\u201378}}</ref>\n\nThe Tazmaniac was put out of action by a legit injury for much of 1995. On July 15, during a tag team match [[2 Cold Scorpio]] and [[Dean Malenko]] delivered a [[Professional wrestling double-team maneuvers#Aided piledriver|spike piledriver]] to him, and though he knew it was about to be performed, he did not have time to properly protect himself. As he explained on the DVD documentary ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]'', \"I landed right on my forehead and just jacked my whole neck back and that was it.\" The neck injury was so bad that, according to [[Tommy Dreamer]], hospital staff couldn't believe he'd walked into the hospital where he sought help after the match. Though he was unable to wrestle, Paul Heyman continued to pay him per their oral agreement, forging a loyalty between the men.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n==== Rise to superstardom (1995\u20131996) ====\nFollowing his neck injury, Taz made appearances with [[The Steiner Brothers]], even standing in their corner during matches with [[The Eliminators]] and getting physical with [[Jason Knight|Jason]]. It was at the [[November to Remember (1995)|November to Remember]] event, when Taz turned heel and joined up with referee [[Bill Alfonso]]. Working as the special referee for Alfonso's match with ECW commissioner [[Tod Gordon]], Taz refused to count to three and assaulted Gordon, then making the count for Alfonso. In his post-match promo, he claimed that no one was looking after him while he was injured and that no one cared (though Heyman was still paying him, the [[kayfabe]] story was that he had been forgotten and that Alfonso was the one helping him keep food on his family's table). He was also angry that Sabu was brought back in that very night.\n\nTaz returned to the ring on December 19, 1995 at Holiday Hell with a new look and wrestling style. The new character had him clad in a black/orange [[wiktionary:singlet|singlet]] and exhibiting a more physically intense in-ring style, focusing his offense on mat wrestling and [[suplex]]es (inspired by working with The Steiner Brothers), which announcer [[Joey Styles]] dubbed ''[[#In wrestling|Taz-Plexes]]'', earning him the nickname \"The Human Suplex Machine\". He also debuted his ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Half nelson choke|Tazmission]]''/Katahajime finishing maneuver, causing opponents to [[Submission (combat sport)|tap out]] to signal their submission as in [[mixed martial arts]] instead of nodding their head or vocally saying \"yes\". This quirk was soon picked up by other companies throughout the country.<ref>{{cite episode|title=12/17/95|series=History of ECW|network=[[WWE Classics On Demand]]| airdate=2007-08-14}}</ref> Heading into the summer, Taz began feuding with Tommy Dreamer, joining up with [[Brian Lee (wrestler)|Brian Lee]] to face Dreamer and [[Terry Gordy]] and later Dreamer and [[\"Dr. Death\" Steve Williams]]. Taz also developed a friendship with The Eliminators, based on mutual respect, and they occasionally involved themselves in his matches. [[Perry Saturn]] and Taz were both trainers at ECW's [[House of Hardcore]] wrestling school. For a while, some of the students, including Mako and [[Chris Chetti]], would accompany Taz and Alfonso to the ring as a faction known as Team Taz.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\nAt [[November to Remember (1996)|November to Remember]], things seemed to come full circle, as Taz stormed to the ring and interrupted Styles and \"stole Paul E.'s thunder\" by announcing that there would be a \"big show in the first quarter of the new year\", basically telling the fans in attendance that ECW's first [[pay-per-view]] was on the horizon. At that \"big show\", he guaranteed that Sabu would finally face him. Later that night, he came out to force Scorpio to leave the ring and went on an angry tirade, abusing Bob Artese and holding him hostage in the ring. Taz demanded Sabu come out and face him, and twice even led the crowd in a \"Sabu, Sabu\" chant to get him to enter the ring.  Several officials and wrestlers came out and Taz eventually got his hands on Paul E. The lights went out and when they came back on, Sabu was in the ring, across from Taz. This was the first time they had been in the ring together since early 1995. Before they could lock up, the lights went out again.\n\nDuring Sabu's match, where he teamed with [[Rob Van Dam]] to face The Eliminators and [[The Gangstas]] in a three-way dance, Taz attempted to attack his former partner, but Van Dam saved Sabu and was choked out in the aisle. This distraction caused Sabu to get hit with ''Total Elimination'' and his team lost. Taz also began a mini-feud with Rob Van Dam, dominating him in every match and was also out for a short time to get surgery on his injured shoulder. As 1996 ended and 1997 began, Taz and Sabu continued to try getting at one another, with no actual contact.\n\n==== World Television Champion (1997\u20131998) ====\nEarly in 1997, the antagonism between Sabu and Taz was growing, as Taz attacked Sabu's partner, Rob Van Dam, costing the team matches with The Eliminators and other teams. In the months leading to ECW's [[ECW Barely Legal|first pay-per-view]], Taz would choke out low-level wrestlers with the ''Tazmission'' due to viewing his matches as secondary to his rivalry with Sabu. He then dominated another series of matches with Van Dam before meeting Sabu at [[ECW Barely Legal|Barely Legal]], where Taz defeated him with the ''Tazmission'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1997b.html#041397|title=Barely Legal 1997 results| accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> only to have his [[Manager (professional wrestling)|manager]] [[Bill Alfonso]] [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Turn|turn]] on him and join Sabu and his partner [[Rob Van Dam]].<ref name=\"slambio\"/> In response, Taz began teaming with [[Chris Candido]] to face Sabu and Van Dam.\n\nTwo months later at [[Wrestlepalooza (1997)|Wrestlepalooza]], Taz lost to Sabu in the rematch, marking his first loss since 1995. However, later in the night, he won the World Television Championship from [[Shane Douglas]] to begin his second reign.<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/> He defended the title against all comers, including Douglas, [[Lance Storm]], [[John Kronus]], [[Al Snow]], [[Jerry Lynn]] and [[Chris Candido]]. Throughout late 1997, Taz began feuding with The Triple Threat in addition to Sabu and Van Dam, where he sometimes teamed up with [[Tommy Dreamer]] during the feud. At [[November to Remember (1997)|November to Remember]], he issued a challenge to World Heavyweight Champion Bam Bam Bigelow. The two would eventually meet, after Bigelow turned on Taz in a match against Shane Douglas and Chris Candido. Taz would ultimately lose the title to [[Bam Bam Bigelow]] at [[Living Dangerously (1998)|Living Dangerously]] on March 1, 1998.\n\nAfter losing the World Television Championship, Taz was elevated into the World Heavyweight Championship picture. In May 1998, with Shane Douglas injured and unable to wrestle, Taz was given an old World Television Championship belt painted orange\u2014his trademark color\u2014and began [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#Promo|cutting promos]], declaring himself the [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship|FTW Heavyweight Champion]] at [[It Ain't Seinfeld]]. Though the championship was unsanctioned [[Kayfabe|in storyline]], it was defended at ECW shows until Douglas was healthy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1998c.html#080298|title=Heat Wave 1998 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just before winning the World Heavyweight Championship, Taz \"gave\" the FTW Heavyweight Title to long-time foe Sabu in a match where he physically pulled Sabu on top of him to allow him to get the pin.<ref name=\"SolieFTW\">{{cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/ftwecw.html|title=Fuck The World title history|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Solie's Title Histories}}</ref>\n\n==== World Heavyweight Champion and departure (1999) ====\nTaz finally defeated Shane Douglas for the World Heavyweight Championship at [[Guilty as Charged (1999)|Guilty as Charged]], thus ending Douglas' year-long reign.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999a.html#011099|title=Guilty as Charged 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz was supposed to defend the title against [[Chris Candido]] in his first televised title defense at [[House Party (1999)|House Party]] but Douglas attacked Candido before the match and took his place, whom Taz defeated to retain the title in his first successful title defense. He would then begin a feud with Sabu over Taz's World Heavyweight Championship and Sabu's FTW Heavyweight Championship. The rivalry culminated in a title unification match at the [[Living Dangerously (1999)|Living Dangerously]] pay-per-view, where Taz defeated Sabu to unify the FTW Heavyweight Championship into the World Heavyweight Championship. He would begin his next rivalry with Chris Candido, whom he defeated to retain the title at [[CyberSlam (1999)|CyberSlam]]. The two were scheduled to a rematch at [[Hardcore Heaven (1999)|Hardcore Heaven]], which Taz quickly won. However, he was attacked by [[Dudley Boyz]] after the match, leading to a title defense against [[Bubba Ray Dudley|Buh Buh Ray Dudley]] in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|falls count anywhere match]] in the main event later that night, which Taz won to retain the title. Taz then successfully defended the title against Candido on the June 4 episode of ''Hardcore TV'' to end the rivalry.\n\nTaz made his next successful title defense against [[Spike Dudley]] in a Falls Count Anywhere match on the June 25 episode of ''Hardcore TV''. He would begin feuding with the members of [[Steve Corino]]'s [[The Network (professional wrestling)|new rising stable]], primarily [[Yoshihiro Tajiri]]. Taz successfully defended the World Heavyweight Championship against Tajiri at [[Hostile City Showdown (1999)|Hostile City Showdown]], the [[Heat Wave (1999)|Heat Wave]] pay-per-view and the September 3 episode of ''[[ECW on TNN]]''. During that time, Taz signed with the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]], losing the title as the first man eliminated in a [[Professional wrestling match types#Basic elimination matches|three-way dance]] at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999c.html#091999|title=Anarchy Rulz 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher= Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> This ended his eight-month reign at 252 days. As he walked out of the ring, a large portion of the ECW locker room joined him on the entrance ramp to give him an emotional sendoff. After being off of ECW television for most of the fall, he wrestled one final match as an ECW performer at [[November to Remember (1999)|November to Remember]], losing to [[Rob Van Dam]] via [[Pin (wrestling)|pinfall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/ecw/results/1999d.html#110799|title=November to Remember 1999 results|accessdate=July 22, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Taz's final televised match in ECW aired on the November 13 episode of ''Hardcore TV'', in which he received a rematch against Mike Awesome for the World Heavyweight Championship, which he lost. In the DVD ''The Rise and Fall of ECW'', Taz said that he signed with the WWE because he was in the top of the company and he lost his passion.<ref name=\"Houseofhardcore\"/>\n\n=== World Wrestling Federation/Entertainment (2000-2009)===\n==== Hardcore Champion, feud with Jerry Lawler and The Alliance (2000\u20132002) ====\n{{Main|The Invasion (professional wrestling)|l1=The Invasion|The Alliance (professional wrestling)|l2=The Alliance}}\nAfter being contacted by the [[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]] (WWF) and [[World Championship Wrestling]] (WCW) in 1999,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081021065026/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0FCO/is_3_2/ai_65858907/pg_2?tag=artBody;col1|url-status=dead|archive-date=2008-10-21|title=Defection Inspection|last=Anderson|first=Steve|accessdate=July 17, 2008|date=October 2000|publisher=Wrestling Digest}}</ref> Taz debuted for the WWF, with the slightly modified ring name Tazz, at the [[Royal Rumble (2000)|2000 Royal Rumble]] with a win over the previously undefeated [[Kurt Angle]] at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/rumble.html#00|title=Royal Rumble 2000 results|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Just a few months after Tazz arrived in the WWF, [[Mike Awesome]], the man he had lost the ECW World Heavyweight Championship to at [[Anarchy Rulz (1999)|Anarchy Rulz]], secretly signed with WCW. Legal wrangling by Paul Heyman prevented Awesome from taking the championship belt with him, and in a bizarre piece of professional wrestling history, ECW and WWF officials agreed to have Tazz, a WWF wrestler, make a surprise appearance at an ECW show to defeat Awesome, a WCW wrestler, for the ECW World Heavyweight Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2007/02/19/3645984.html|title=Mike Awesome found dead|last= Oliver|first=Greg|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Sports]]}}</ref> Tazz held the title for ten days before losing it to [[Tommy Dreamer]], during which time he wore it on various WWF shows, including an episode of ''[[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]]'' where he lost to the [[WWE Championship|WWF Champion]] [[Triple H]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |title=SmackDown! results \u2013 2000 |accessdate=July 23, 2007 |publisher=Online World of Wrestling |quote=April 20, 2000[...]WWF World Champion, Triple H, b ECW World Champion, Tazz |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081012210938/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/_2000/ |archivedate=October 12, 2008 }}</ref> However, [[Vince McMahon]] later expressed some regret over [[Professional wrestling booker|booking]] Tazz to lose to Triple H.<ref>{{cite video|date=November 16, 2004|title=[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]|medium=DVD|publisher=[[WWE Home Video]]}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the ECW World Heavyweight Championship, Tazz was placed into contention for the [[WWE Intercontinental Championship|Intercontinental Championship]], but never won the title. In the summer, after taking time off for an arm injury, he was turned into a [[Heel (professional wrestling)|villainous character]] and placed into a feud with [[color commentator]] [[Jerry Lawler]].<ref name=\"slamint\"/> The feud included matches at [[SummerSlam (2000)|SummerSlam]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/summer.html#2000|title=SummerSlam 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> and [[Unforgiven 2000|Unforgiven]], which they split.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlinghistory.com/supercards/usa/wwf/unforgiven.html#2000|title=Unforgiven 2000 results|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Pro Wrestling History}}</ref> Tazz was only able to pick up the Unforgiven win when he received help from [[Raven (wrestler)|Raven]], who had returned to the company. Afterwards, the duo formed a [[tag team]] that lasted until November.\n\nWhen the [[The Invasion (professional wrestling)|Invasion]] angle began, Tazz acted as \"the voice of the [[The Alliance (professional wrestling)|WCW/ECW Alliance]]\", sticking up for them and speaking on their behalf whenever possible. He eventually left the [[Glossary of professional wrestling terms#S|stable]] after the leader [[Steve Austin|Stone Cold Steve Austin]] criticized his decision to stay on commentary rather than help ECW owner [[Stephanie McMahon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011108.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 8, 2001|accessdate=July 23, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref>\n\n==== Commentator (2002\u20132009) ====\nWith injuries mounting,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/shows/ecw/archive/01082008/articles/tazzshoots|title=Tazz shoots again|accessdate=January 11, 2008|author=Tazz|publisher=WWE|date=January 10, 2008}}</ref> Tazz began performing part-time commentary on ''[[WWE Heat|Sunday Night Heat]]'' in October 2000. He joined the ''SmackDown!'' team in February 2001 after Jerry Lawler quit the company, after calling his first [[pay-per-view]] on [[No Way Out (2001)|No Way Out]] with [[Jim Ross]], as well as becoming one of the trainers for the joint WWF/[[MTV]] produced reality series ''[[WWE Tough Enough|Tough Enough]]''.<ref name=\"slamint\">{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.ca/SlamWrestlingBiosT/tazz_01aug-can.html|title=Tazz talks: ECW, Tough Enough, WWF|last=Kapur|first=Bob |accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|Slam! Wrestling]]}}</ref> Lawler returned to the company on November 19, 2001 and resumed his place as commentator, with Tazz becoming both a wrestler and a commentator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/011122.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 November 22, 2001|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling}}</ref> In January 2002, he and [[Spike Dudley]] won the [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|Tag Team Championship]],<ref>{{cite news|author=Michael McAvennie|title=WWE The Yearbook: 2003 Edition|publisher=Pocket Books|year=2003|pages=13\u201316}}</ref> holding it for over a month before losing it to [[Billy and Chuck]].<ref name=\"WT-WWFTT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wrestling-titles.com/wwf/wwf-t.html|title=WWWF / WWF / WWE World Tag Team Title|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Wrestling-Titles}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Tazz.jpg|left|thumb|250x250px|Tazz signing autographs in 2006]]\nWhen World Wrestling Entertainment [[WWE Brand Extension|split into two brands]], Tazz was put on the [[WWE SmackDown|SmackDown!]] brand, where he resumed his color commentator duties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|title=SmackDown! results \u2013 April 4, 2002|accessdate=July 24, 2007|publisher=Online World of Wrestling|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090917154817/http://www.onlineworldofwrestling.com/results/smackdown/020404.html|archivedate=September 17, 2009}}</ref> Not long after he retired from the ring, he became a full-time broadcaster.<ref name=Tazzvision>{{cite web|url= http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/Wrestling/2005/05/30/1063493.html|title=Tuning into Tazzvision|last=Zerr|first=Scott|accessdate =July 24, 2007|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Wrestling]]}}</ref> He co-hosted ''SmackDown!'' for World Wrestling Entertainment until a third brand, [[ECW (WWE brand)|ECW]], was introduced in 2006, at which point he became the color commentator for that show.<ref name=\"WWEProfile\"/> He was also the co-host, with Joey Styles, of ''History of [[Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'' on [[WWE 24/7 Classics]], a show that re-airs archived episodes of the original ECW's weekly television programs. Before and during episodes he and Styles provide insight into the storylines, inner workings, and general ambiance of ECW at the time\u2014as they remember it.\n\nIn February 2006, Tazz and his ''SmackDown!'' broadcasting partner, [[Michael Cole (wrestling)|Michael Cole]], hosted a week-long trial run of a show on [[Howard 100 and Howard 101|Howard 101]] on [[Sirius Satellite Radio]], but the show was not picked up. He also hosted a talk show on [[WNYL (FM)|92.3 Free FM]] at sporadic intervals between late summer 2006 and early 2007, but it was not picked up and the station changed formats, replacing all post morning programming with music. On June 11, 2006, Tazz wrestled his final match to date, defeating Jerry Lawler at [[ECW One Night Stand (2006)|ECW One Night Stand]].<ref>{{cite web|title=ECW One Night Stand PPV Results 6/11/06 New York City, New York|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2006/1150081251.shtml| publisher=WrestleView|first=Adam|last=Martin|date=June 11, 2006|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nDuring the recording of the April 29, 2008 episode of ''[[ECW (WWE)|ECW]]'', Tazz's broadcast partner [[Mike Adamle]] abruptly walked off set prior to the main event. Moments later, after reading the promo for the upcoming pay-per-view, Tazz walked out as well, leaving the main event with no commentators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2008/04/30/5428941.html|title=ECW: Announcing follies overshadow decent show|first=Matt|last=Bishop|accessdate=April 30, 2008|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer|SLAM! Sports]]}}</ref> On December 13, 2010, Tazz joined Right After Wrestling and said that it \"pisses him off\" when companies try to re-create the original ECW. He stated that the original ECW worked because \"It was that era, that group of people, that leader in Paul Heyman. We were that little engine that could.\"<ref>[http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 Podcasts | The Score] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120715182953/http://radio.thescore.com/episodes/taz-right-after-wrestling-dec-13-2010 |date=2012-07-15 }}. Radio.thescore.com (December 13, 2010). Retrieved on 2011-11-29.</ref>\n\nIn August 2008, Tazz filled in for [[Mick Foley]] as a color commentator on the SmackDown brand, while Raw wrestler [[Matt Striker]] filled in for Tazz on the ECW brand. When Foley left the company, Tazz became the permanent color commentator for the SmackDown brand once again. On April 3, 2009, Tazz left WWE when his contract expired. His WWE.com profile was moved from the active SmackDown roster list to the alumni list for a short time before being completely removed, confirming his departure from the company.\n\n=== Total Nonstop Action Wrestling (2009\u20132015) ===\n[[File:Tazz and Mike Tenay.jpg|thumb|Taz (left) with his commentary partner, [[Mike Tenay]] in July 2010]]\nAt [[Victory Road (2009)|Victory Road]], Senercia, under his Taz ring name, made his official [[Total Nonstop Action Wrestling]] (TNA) debut during [[Samoa Joe]]'s match against [[Sting (wrestler)|Sting]], revealing himself to be Joe's [[Kayfabe|on-screen]] adviser and consequently a [[heel (professional wrestling)|heel]] as well as an ally of the [[The Main Event Mafia|Main Event Mafia]]. The match ending was booked as Taz's presence enabling Joe to recover from Sting's ''[[Sharpshooter (professional wrestling)|Scorpion Deathlock]]'' and win the match via submission after applying the ''[[Professional wrestling holds#Rear naked choke|Coquina Clutch]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Victory Road PPV Results \u2013 7/19/09|url=http://www.wrestleview.com/news2009/1248058721.php|last=Martin|first=Adam|date=July 19, 2009|work=WrestleView|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn the August 20, 2009 episode of ''[[Impact! (TV series)|Impact!]]'', Taz replaced [[Don West (wrestling)|Don West]] as the promotion's color commentator and also became a [[Face (professional wrestling)|face]] upon stating that he was only loosely associated with the Mafia and that he had taught Joe everything he knew and that it was now up to Joe to use his newfound skills.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/font_color_770000_KELLER_S_TAKE_font_11/article_34814.shtml|title=Keller's TNA Impact report 8/20: Results, star ratings, thoughts, observations, quotebook|authorlink=Wade Keller|last=Keller|first=Wade|date=August 27, 2009|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Impact: Blueprint gets the tables|url=http://slam.canoe.ca/Slam/Wrestling/2009/08/21/10541866.html?cid=rsssportswrestling|last=Sokol|first=Bryan|author2=Sokol, Chris |date=August 21, 2009|work=Slam! Sports|publisher=[[Canadian Online Explorer]]|accessdate=July 15, 2010}}</ref> In May 2012, Taz began appearing as a judge in the monthly [[TNA Gut Check|Gut Check]] segment on ''Impact Wrestling''.<ref name=\"TNA3May\">{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_61084.shtml|title=Turner's TNA Impact Wrestling Results 5/3: Roode and RVD pick opponents for each other, Gut Check fall-out, Flair calls out Hogan|author=Turner, Scott|publisher=[[Pro Wrestling Torch Newsletter|PWTorch.com]]|date=May 4, 2012|accessdate=September 29, 2012}}</ref><!-- DO NOT ADD WEEK BY WEEK EVENTS, RUMORS OR SPECULATION. THIS INCLUDES ANNOUNCED MATCHES THAT HAVE NOT YET OCCURRED. WIKIPEDIA IS NOT A NEWS SITE BUT AN ONLINE ENCYCLOPEDIA. Please see the articles \"Wikipedia:What Wikipedia is not\" and \"Wikipedia:Guide to writing better articles\" for more information. -->\n\nOn the January 17, 2013 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz was a [[groomsman]] at the wedding between [[Mark LoMonaco|Bully Ray]] and [[Brooke Hogan]]. As Ray and Brooke exchanged their vows, Taz interrupted the ceremony and proclaimed himself to be a member of [[Aces & Eights]] after revealing a [[kutte]] underneath his coat, turning heel again in the process. Following his revelation, Aces & Eights ambushed the ceremony and attacked Ray, his groomsmen [[Tommy Dreamer]] and [[Spike Dudley|Brother Runt]] and Brooke's father [[Hulk Hogan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_67961.shtml|title= KELLER'S TNA IMPACT REPORT 1/17: The Bully Ray-Brooke Hogan Wedding Episode \u2013 What happened? Did Hulk accompany Brooke? Did the wedding end without a hitch?|date=January 17, 2013|last=Keller|first=Wade|accessdate=January 17, 2013|work=Pro Wrestling Torch}}</ref> The following week on ''Impact Wrestling'', Taz revealed that he joined Aces & Eights because of his desire to be a member of a group that adheres to a higher power.<ref name=TazReason>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_68117.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 1/24: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of Hardy vs. Daniels TNA Title match, Teflon Taz, wedding fall-out (updated w/Box Score)|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref> On the November 21 episode of ''Impact Wrestling'', Aces & Eights was forced to disband after Bully Ray lost to [[Ken Anderson (wrestler)|Mr. Anderson]], which also saw Anderson retain his career in TNA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/artman2/publish/tnaimpact/article_74692.shtml|title=PWTorch.com - CALDWELL'S TNA IMPACT RESULTS 11/21: Complete \"virtual-time\" coverage of \"Turning Point\" Impact - TNA Title tournament continues, Bully vs. Anderson, more|website=www.pwtorch.com}}</ref>\n\nOn April 15, 2015, it was  officially announced that Taz had departed TNA.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=JohnGaburick|author=John Gaburick|number=588450682002255873|date=15 April 2015|title=After 5+ years TNA &amp; Taz have mutually decided to part ways. A champ in the ring &amp; on the mic, we wish him nothing but success! @OfficialTAZ}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=OfficialTAZ|author=TAZ|number=588450023613988864|date=15 April 2015|title=Like to thank TNA Wrestling for the opportunity to apply my craft for past several years. Best wishes to them in the future.}}</ref>\n\n=== Return to WWE (2016) ===\nIn November 2016, Tazz made an appearance on the [[WWE Network]] special, ''The Authentic Untold Story of ECW'', alongside former ECW management Paul Hayman and wrestlers Bubba Ray Dudley, D-Von Dudley, and Tommy Dreamer. In the one-hour special hosted by [[Corey Graves]], the guests talked about their experiences in ECW and the promotion's legacy on professional wrestling.\n\n=== All Elite Wrestling (2019\u2013present) ===\nOn October 12, 2019, Taz made a guest appearance for [[All Elite Wrestling]] (AEW), where he appeared on the October 22nd edition of ''[[AEW Dark]]'' as a guest commentator.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrestlinginc.com/news/2019/10/taz-to-guest-commentate-on-this-week-aew-dark-660674/|title=Taz To Guest Commentate On This Week's AEW Dark|publisher=Wrestling Inc.}}</ref> On November 9, 2019, Taz made his guest appearance during [[AEW Full Gear|Full Gear]] as the pre-show commentator. On the January 1, 2020 episode of ''[[AEW Dynamite]]'', Taz made his ''Dynamite'' debut on commentary filling in for [[Tony Schiavone]]. On January 16, 2020, it was announced that Taz had officially signed a multi-year deal with AEW, and he is set to be a member of the AEW broadcast team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sescoops.com/taz-signs-multi-year-deal-with-aew/amp/|title=Taz Signs Multi-Year Deal With AEW|work=SEScoops.com|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Professional wrestling style and persona ==\nTazz's character was influenced by [[The Missing Link (wrestler)|The Missing Link]], [[The Steiner Brothers]] and [[Wild Samoans]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-talks-early-disagreement-vince-mcmahon/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Talks About An Early Disagreement With Vince McMahon}}</ref> Tazz is nicknamed the \"Human Suplex Machine\" due to his wide array of suplex variations he would utilise in matches. His finishing move, the ''Tazmission'', is a half nelson choke with bodyscissors. He also sometimes combined this submission with a suplex, creating a half nelson choke suplex, called the ''Tazmission-Plex''.<ref name=\"OwW\"/><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.wwe.com/classics/classic-lists/the-50-coolest-maneuvers-of-all-time/page-16 |title=the 50 coolest maneuvers of all time|date=February 21, 2014|accessdate=March 13, 2014|publisher=WWE}}</ref> He has also claimed to have named the T-Bone Suplex.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://411mania.com/wrestling/taz-says-named-t-bone-suplex/|title=411MANIA|website=Taz Says He Named The T-Bone Suplex}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nHe has a [[tattoo]] of the [[Tasmanian Devil (Looney Tunes)|Looney Tunes Tasmanian Devil]] on his upper right bicep accompanied by the legend Taz. His action figures produced by [[Jakks Pacific]] does not include the character, but does include the name. He has a self designed tattoo on his left lower bicep. Senerchia played [[Secondary school|high school]] [[high school football|football]]. Senerchia also studied [[judo]] prior to entering the professional wrestling circuit, reaching a second-degree black belt.<ref name=tazz73>Loverro, Thom (2006). ''[[The Rise and Fall of ECW]]''. Pocket Books. {{ISBN|978-1-41-651312-4}}. p. 73</ref>  He is a fan of the [[New York Mets]], [[New York Knicks]], [[Philadelphia 76ers]], and the [[New York Jets]].{{citation needed|date=September 2018}}\n\n==In other media==\nBeginning in 2018, Senercia was a nationally syndicated morning radio personality, co-hosting ''Taz and The Moose'' with Marc \"The Moose\" Malusis on [[CBS Sports Radio]] weekdays from 6-9 a.m. Eastern.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cbssports.radio.com/shows/taz-and-moose|title=Taz & The Moose - CBS Sports Radio}}</ref> In December 2019, Senercia announced he was leaving the show.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://barrettsportsmedia.com/2019/12/17/taz-to-exit-cbs-sports-radio/|title=Taz To Exit CBS Sports Radio|date=2019-12-17|website=Barrett Sports Media|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>  \n\nSenercia also has his own podcast, called ''The Taz Show'', (formerly known as ''The Human Podcast Machine)'', where he discusses the latest in the professional wrestling world. The show has since discontinued. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radio.com/taz-show|title=The Taz Show|date=2018-04-30|website=RADIO.COM|language=en|access-date=2020-01-22}}</ref>\n\nSenercia (as Tazz) appears as a playable character in ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2007|SmackDown vs. Raw 2007]]'' and ''[[WWE SmackDown vs. Raw 2009|SmackDown vs. Raw 2009]]''.\n\n== Championships and accomplishments ==\n\n=== Amateur wrestling ===\n* Empire States Heavyweight Championship<ref>Noted by [[Joey Styles]] during the [[November to Remember 1997|1997 November to Remember]] broadcast</ref>\n\n=== Professional wrestling ===\n* '''[[Century Wrestling Alliance]]'''\n** [[CWA Cruiserweight Championship|CWA Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[CWA Cruiserweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"slambio\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.solie.org/titlehistories/lhtcwa2.html|title=Solie's Title Histories: CWA - CENTURY WRESTLING ALLIANCE|website=www.solie.org}}</ref>\n*'''[[Extreme Championship Wrestling|Eastern/Extreme Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship]] ([[ECW FTW Heavyweight Championship#Title history|2 times]])<ref name=\"SolieFTW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Heavyweight Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Heavyweight Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWHW\"/>\n** [[ECW World Television Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Television Champions|2 times]])<ref name=\"WT-ECWTV\"/>\n** [[ECW World Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of ECW World Tag Team Champions|3 times]]) \u2013 with [[Kevin Sullivan (wrestler)|Kevin Sullivan]] (2)<sup>1</sup> and [[Sabu (wrestler)|Sabu]] (1)<ref name=\"WT-ECWTT\"/>\n** Third [[Triple Crown (professional wrestling)#List of ECW Triple Crown Champions|ECW Triple Crown Champion]]\n* '''[[International World Class Championship Wrestling]]'''\n** [[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship]] ([[IWCCW Light Heavyweight Championship#Title history|1 time]])<ref name=\"WT-IWCCW\"/>\n* '''''[[Pro Wrestling Illustrated]]'''''\n** Ranked No. 10 of the 500 best singles wrestlers in the [[PWI 500]] in 1999<ref>{{cite web|url=http://profightdb.com/pwi-500/1999.html|title=Pro Wrestling Illustrated (PWI) 500 for 1999|accessdate=November 24, 2015|publisher=The Internet Wrestling Database}}</ref>\n**PWI ranked him No. 147 of the top 500 singles wrestlers of the \"[[PWI Years]]\" in 2003\n* '''[[WWE|World Wrestling Federation]]'''\n** [[WWE Hardcore Championship|WWF Hardcore Championship]] ([[List of WWE Hardcore Champions|3 times]])<sup>2</sup><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/hardcore-championship|title=Hardcore Championship|website=WWE}}</ref>\n** [[World Tag Team Championship (WWE)|WWF Tag Team Championship]] ([[List of World Tag Team Champions (WWE)|1 time]]) \u2013 with [[Spike Dudley]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|title=World Tag Team Championship \u2013 Tazz & Spike Dudley|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121024180601/http://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/worldtagteam/3044541321115|archivedate=2012-10-24}}</ref>\n*'''''[[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]'''''\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Gimmick|Worst Gimmick]] (2013) <small>[[Aces & Eights]]</small><ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=35}}</ref>\n** [[List of Wrestling Observer Newsletter awards#Worst Television Announcer|Worst Television Announcer]] (2013)<ref>{{cite journal|last=Meltzer|first=Dave|authorlink=Dave Meltzer|date=January 27, 2014|title=Jan 27 2014 Wrestling Observer Newsletter: 2013 Annual awards issue, best in the world in numerous categories, plus all the news in pro-wrestling and MMA over the past week and more|journal=[[Dave Meltzer#Wrestling Observer Newsletter|Wrestling Observer Newsletter]]|location=[[Campbell, California]]|issn=1083-9593|url=http://www.f4wonline.com/component/content/article/110-wrestling-observer-newsletter/35067-jan-27-2014-wrestling-observer-newsletter-2013-annual-awards-issue-best-in-the-world-in-numerous-categories-plus-all-the-news-in-pro-wrestling-and-mma-over-the-past-week-and-more|page=26}}</ref>\n*'''Victory Championship Wrestling'''\n**VCW Hall of Fame (Class of 2018)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Peter Senerchia|Tazz}}\n* {{IMDb name|name = Peter Senerchia}}\n* {{WWE superstar|name = Tazz}}\n* {{Professional wrestling profiles}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20131103092937/http://www.impactwrestling.com/roster/Wrestler-Roster/item/1622-taz TNA profile]\n\n{{Navboxes|\n|list1=\n{{All Elite Wrestling}}\n{{Aces & Eights}}\n{{ECW Championship}}\n{{ECW World Television Championship}}\n{{ECW World Tag Team Championship}}\n{{Grand Slam-Triple Crown Champions}}\n{{WWE Hardcore Championship}}\n{{World Tag Team Championship (WWE)}}\n}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taz}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Aces and Eights members]]\n[[Category:All Elite Wrestling personnel]]\n[[Category:American color commentators]]\n[[Category:American male professional wrestlers]]\n[[Category:American people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:American podcasters]]\n[[Category:ECW Heavyweight Champions/ECW World Heavyweight Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Tag Team Champions]]\n[[Category:ECW World Television Champions]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:LIU Post alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestlers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling announcers]]\n[[Category:Professional wrestling trainers]]\n[[Category:The Alliance (professional wrestling) members]]\n[[Category:The Dangerous Alliance members]]\n[[Category:The ECW Originals members]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changingshort descriptionfrom \"American radio personality, color commentator and retire