esMachine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smspower.org/Scans/TGM-Magazine-Issue14?gallerypage=75 |title=TGM - Issue 14 - United Kingdom Magazine - Scans |publisher=SMS Power! |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]''\n| \n| \n| 71%<ref>''[[:fr:Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]'', issue 32, p. 173</ref>\n| \n| 75%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_44761 |title=Double Dragon review from Joystick 15 (Apr 1991) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| 91%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_44177 |title=Double Dragon review from Joystick 9 (Oct 1990) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Mean Machines]]''\n| \n| 70%<ref name=\"MeanMachines\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smspower.org/Scans/MeanMachinesSega-Magazine-Issue01?gallerypage=133 |title=Mean Machines Sega - Issue 01 - United Kingdom Magazine - Scans |publisher=SMS Power! |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| 59%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meanmachinesmag.co.uk/review/296/double-dragon.php |title=Double Dragon - Sega Megadrive - Mean Machines review |publisher=Meanmachinesmag.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| 83%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.meanmachinesmag.co.uk/review/381/double-dragon.php |title=Double Dragon - Nintendo Gameboy - Mean Machines review |publisher=Meanmachinesmag.co.uk |date=2015-05-28 |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Europress|Mega Action]]''\n| \n| \n| 82%<ref>''Mega Action'', issue 1, p. 64, [[Europress]]</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[MegaTech]]''\n| \n| \n| 53%<ref>MegaTech rating, [[EMAP]], issue 6, page 77, June 1992</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Mega Zone]]''\n| \n| \n| \n| 85%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_47388 |title=Double Dragon review from MegaZone 29 (Jul 1993) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sega Power]]''\n| \n| 85%<ref>''[[Sega Power]]'', issue 23, p. 41</ref>\n| 13%<ref>''[[Sega Power]]'', issue 31, pp. 30-31</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sega Pro]]''\n| \n| 77%<ref>''[[Sega Pro]]'', issue 2, p. 45</ref>\n| 72%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerankings.com/genesis/586145-double-dragon/articles.html |title=Double Dragon Reviews and Articles for Genesis |publisher=GameRankings |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n|-\n| ''[[Sinclair User]]''\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| 51%<ref>[http://www.worldofspectrum.org/showmag.cgi?mag=SinclairUser/Issue082/Pages/SinclairUser08200055.jpg World of Spectrum - Archive - Magazine viewer<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Your Sinclair]]''\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| 8/10<ref>[http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/doubledragon.htm Double Dragon<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120117215227/http://www.ysrnry.co.uk/articles/doubledragon.htm |date=2012-01-17 }}</ref>\n|-\n! colspan=12 | [[List of Game of the Year awards|Awards]]\n|-\n! Award\n! colspan=11 | Entities\n|-\n| [[Game of the Year]]\n| colspan=11 | ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]''\n|-\n| [[List of video games considered the best|Best Games of<br />All Time]]\n| colspan=11 | ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'',<ref name=EGM2006/> ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'',<ref name=Empire2009/> ''[[Game Informer]]'',<ref name=GI2001/><ref name=GI2009/> [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]],<ref name=G4/> [[GameSpot]],<ref name=GS2006/><br />[[GameRevolution|GamingBolt]],<ref name=GamingBolt/> [[Killer List of Videogames|KLOV]],<ref name=KLOV/> [[Imagine Publishing|NowGamer]],<ref name=NowGamer/> [[Yahoo!]]<ref name=Yahoo/>\n|}\n\nThe original arcade version was well-received upon release. In the August 1987 issue of ''[[Commodore User]]'', Ferdy Hamilton gave it ratings of 9 for graphics, 7 for sound, 9 for toughness, 10 for endurance, and 9 for value, with an overall score of 9 out of 10. He noted the game's popularity, stating that it took him \"about half an hour to get near it in my local [[Amusement arcade|arcade]]\" and \"a brief glance around [[West End of London|West End]] arcades confirmed\" that \"''Double Dragon'' is set to be a massive [[Arcade game|coin-op]] hit.\" He stated that it \"isn't an easy game to play initially\" and requires \"both brain and brawn,\" described the graphics as \"superb, the handling likewise,\" and stated \"the variety of actions, locations and enemies make this a true state of the art Beat 'Em Up, centuries beyond those old Kung Fu games which still litter the arcades.\" He concluded it to be \"a strong contender for hottest beat 'em up yet.\"<ref name=\"CU_ARC\"/> In the July 1987 issue of ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'', Clare Edgeley described the \"Sordid street fights\" as \"great fun when you've got the guts\" and \"if you manage to get hang of the controls.\" She concluded that \"all the ingredients are there for a really addictive, martial arts style kick 'em to bits.\"<ref name=\"CVG_ARC\">[https://archive.org/stream/cvg-magazine-069/CVG_069_Jul_1987#page/n87/mode/2up Double Dragon], ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'', issue 69, July 1987, p. 87</ref> In the October 1987 issue of ''[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]'', the reviewer Tony described it as \"the best game of its kind around\" and \"thoroughly addictive,\" concluding that it is \"depraved, sick, bloodthirsty, violent &ndash; and I love it!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solvalou.com/subpage/arcade_reviews/75/106/double_dragon_review.html |title=Double Dragon arcade game review |publisher=Solvalou.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref> In the November 1987 issue of ''[[Your Sinclair]]'', reviewer Peter Shaw stated that if \"you liked Taito's ''[[Renegade (video game)|Renegade]]'', you'll jest lurve ''Double Dragon'',\" describing it as \"a streetfighting beat 'em up, but much nastier,\" with [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] \"much bigger than the ones in ''Renegade'', which adds to the realism,\" and \"gruesome sound effects,\" concluding that it is \"Great stuff, and really good value, even for 30[[Penny (British decimal coin)|p]] a throw.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solvalou.com/subpage/arcade_reviews/52/106/double_dragon_review.html |title=Double Dragon arcade game review |publisher=Solvalou.com |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n\n[[Toys \"R\" Us]] reported that the NES version of ''Double Dragon'' sold out in its first two weeks on sale in the US.<ref name = \"CGW\">{{Cite news | date = Oct 1988 | last = Worley | first = Joyce | periodical = [[Computer Gaming World]] | title = Video Gaming World's Newswire| page = 48}}</ref> In the UK, [[Mastertronic]]'s home [[PC game|computer game]] ports sold 289,510 units.<ref name=\"RetroGamer\"/>\n\nThe critical reception of the home versions varied depending on the quality of the [[Porting|conversions]]. The Master System port was well received, including positive reviews from ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'',<ref name=\"CVG_SMS\"/> ''[[The Games Machine]]'',<ref name=\"GamesMachine\"/> and ''[[Mean Machines|Mean Machines Sega]]''.<ref name=\"MeanMachines\"/> The NES version was also well received, including a positive review from ''Computer and Video Games''.<ref name=\"CVG_NES\"/>\n\nThe [[home computer]] versions received mixed reviews. ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' noted the limitations of a joystick caused the IBM and C64 ports to use fewer moves than the arcade, the C64 port, in particular, being \"a pale shadow of the original\".<ref name = \"CGW2\">{{Cite news | date = May 1989 | last = Wilson | first = David M. | periodical = [[Computer Gaming World]] | title = Street Lethal | page = 21}}</ref> ''[[Compute!]]'' stated that the Commodore 64 version added a two-player mode, but lacked some arcade features such as moving objects, climbing most ladders, and detailed animation.<ref name=\"poggiali198907\">{{cite news | url=https://archive.org/stream/1989-07-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_110_1989_Jul#page/n61/mode/2up | title=Double Dragon | work=Compute! | date=July 1989 | accessdate=11 November 2013 | author=Poggiali, Len | page=63}}</ref> The Mega Drive version also received mixed reviews; ''[[Mega (magazine)|Mega]]'' placed the game at #10 on their list of the 10 Worst Mega Drive Games of All Time.<ref>Mega magazine issue 1, page 85, [[Future Publishing]], Oct 1992</ref>\n\n''Double Dragon'' has been listed among the [[List of video games considered the best|best video games of all time]], by publications such as ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]'',<ref>{{cite magazine |title=The 10 Best Arcade Games of All Time |magazine=[[Electronic Gaming Monthly]]|issue=100 |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=November 1997|page=130}}</ref><ref name=EGM2006>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.1up.com/features/egm-200-greatest-videogames |title=The Greatest 200 Videogames of Their Time |date=February 6, 2006 |magazine=Electronic Gaming Monthly |accessdate=November 19, 2013 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6CbXoDSo2?url=http://www.1up.com/features/egm-200-greatest-videogames |archivedate=December 2, 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]]'',<ref name=Empire2009>[https://web.archive.org/web/20110515221956/http://www.empireonline.com/100greatestgames/ The 100 Greatest Games], ''[[Empire (film magazine)|Empire]]'', 2009</ref> and ''[[Game Informer]]'',<ref name=GI2001>[http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2009/11/16/game-informer-s-top-100-games-of-all-time-circa-issue-100.aspx?PostPageIndex=1 Game Informer's Top 100 Games of All Time (Circa Issue 100)], ''[[Game Informer]]'', 2001</ref><ref name=GI2009>[http://nintendoeverything.com/game-informers-top-200-games-of-all-time/ Game Informer's Top 200 Games of All Time], ''[[Game Informer]]'', 2009</ref> as well as sites such as [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]],<ref name=G4>[http://www.g4tv.com/top-100/ G4TV\u2019s Top 100 Games], [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]], 2012</ref> [[GameSpot]],<ref name=GS2006>[https://web.archive.org/web/20061223030434/http://www.gamespot.com/gamespot/features/all/greatestgames/index.html The Greatest Games of All Time], [[GameSpot]], 2006</ref> [[GameRevolution|GamingBolt]],<ref name=GamingBolt>[http://gamingbolt.com/top-100-greatest-video-games-ever-made Top 100 greatest video games ever made], [[GameRevolution|GamingBolt]], 2013</ref> [[Killer List of Videogames]],<ref name=KLOV>[http://www.arcade-museum.com/TOP100.php Our List of the Top 100 Coin-Operated Videogames], [[Killer List of Videogames]]</ref> [[Imagine Publishing|NowGamer]],<ref name=NowGamer>100 Greatest Retro Games, NowGamer, [[Imagine Publishing]], 2010: [http://www.nowgamer.com/100-greatest-retro-games-part-1/ part 1], [http://www.nowgamer.com/100-greatest-retro-games-part-2/ part 2], [http://www.nowgamer.com/100-greatest-retro-games-part-3/ part 3], [http://www.nowgamer.com/100-greatest-retro-games-part-4/ part 4]</ref> and [[Yahoo!]]<ref name=Yahoo>[https://web.archive.org/web/20050801002743/http://uk.videogames.games.yahoo.com/specials/100games/ The 100 greatest computer games of all time], [[Yahoo!]], 2006</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\n===Sequels===\n{{further|Double Dragon (series)}}\n\n''Double Dragon'' was followed by two arcade sequels: ''[[Double Dragon II: The Revenge]]'' in [[1988 in video gaming|1988]] and ''[[Double Dragon 3: The Rosetta Stone]]'' in [[1990 in video gaming|1990]]. Both games were also followed by various home versions. Techn\u014ds produced the fourth game in the series titled ''[[Super Double Dragon]]'', released for the [[Super Nintendo Entertainment System|SNES]] in [[1992 in video gaming|1992]]. In [[1993 in video gaming|1993]], a [[crossover (fiction)|crossover]], titled ''[[Battletoads & Double Dragon]]'' and featuring characters from both franchises, was released for various platforms. Also in [[1993 in video gaming|1993]], a [[Game Gear]] game by [[Virgin Interactive|Virgin Games]] was released titled ''Double Dragon: The Revenge of Billy Lee''. Billy and Jimmy also appeared in the 1990 NES game ''[[U.S. Championship V'Ball|Super Spike V'Ball]]''. The characters of Randy and Andy in the 1989 NES game ''[[River City Ransom]]'' are based on Billy and Jimmy; in Japan, they are known as Ry\u016bichi and Ry\u016bji and they appear in later ''[[Kunio-kun]]'' games as well.\n\nAnother game developed by [[WayForward|WayForward Technologies]], ''[[Double Dragon Neon]]'', was released in 2012 for [[Xbox Live Arcade]] and [[PlayStation Network]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/double_dragon_neon/b/ps3/archive/2012/09/11/double-dragon-neon-review-the-lee-brothers-rescue-marian-and-their-dusty-franchise.aspx|title=The Lee Brothers Rescue Marian And Their Dusty Franchise|date=11 September 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Related media===\n''Double Dragon'' also spawned a series of related media in the United States, which includes a six-issue [[comic book|comic]] published by [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] in 1991, an  [[Double Dragon (TV series)|animated TV series]] which ran for two seasons from 1993 to 1995, which influenced a [[Double Dragon (film)|live-action film]] in 1994. In turn, the animated series and movie inspired their respective video game spinoffs as well, both which were fighting games. The cartoon inspired the Tradewest-developed ''[[Double Dragon V: The Shadow Falls]]'', released in [[1994 in video gaming|1994]] for the SNES and Genesis (also ported to the [[Atari Jaguar]]); while characters and plot elements from the movie were adapted into the [[1995 in video gaming|1995]] Techn\u014ds-developed the [[Neo Geo (console)|Neo-Geo]] version of ''[[Double Dragon (Neo-Geo)|Double Dragon]]''.\n\n''Double Dragon'' is one of the video games featured in the manga titled ''Rock'n Game Boy'', by Shigeto Ikehara and Published by Comic BomBom October 1989 to December 1991.\n\nNot specific to any format/system, the original game was used as a clue in the 2015 episode of ''Jeopardy!'' in the category The Marian Kind in the first round on February 17.\n\n===Spin-offs===\nThe boss Abobo is the star of the indie retro game ''[[Abobo's Big Adventure]]''.\n\n==Soundtrack==\nA [[soundtrack]] titled {{nihongo|'''''Original Sound of Double Dragon'''''|\u30aa\u30ea\u30b8\u30ca\u30eb\u30fb\u30b5\u30a6\u30f3\u30c9\u30fb\u30aa\u30d6\u30fb\u30c0\u30d6\u30eb\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3|Orijinaru Saundo obu Daburu Doragon}} was released in Japan by Apollon and composed by Kazunaka Yamane, on February 21, 1988. The soundtrack features [[arrangement|arranged]] versions of the music from the original arcade version. Its catalog number is BY12-5028.\n\n# {{nihongo|Opening (Double Dragon)|\u30aa\u30fc\u30d7\u30cb\u30f3\u30b0\uff08\u53cc\u622a\u9f8d\uff09|\u014cpuningu (Daburu Doragon)}}\n# {{nihongo|The City Slums (The Black Warriors Arrive)|\u30b9\u30e9\u30e0\u8857\uff08\u30d6\u30e9\u30c3\u30af\u30a6\u30a9\u30ea\u30a2\u30fc\u30ba\u51fa\u73fe\uff09|Suramu Machi (Burakku Uori\u0101zu Shutsugen)}}\n# {{nihongo|The Industrial Area (The Great Fray)|\u5de5\u5834\u5730\u5e2f\uff08\u5927\u4e71\u95d8\uff09|K\u014dj\u014dchitai (Dairant\u014d)}}\n# {{nihongo|After the Battle|\u95d8\u3044\u306e\u3042\u3068\u3067|Tatakai no Atode}}\n# {{nihongo|Setting Off (A New Battle)|\u65c5\u7acb\u3061\uff08\u65b0\u305f\u306a\u308b\u95d8\u3044\uff09|Tabidachi (Aratanaru Tatakai}}\n# {{nihongo|The Woods|\u68ee\u6797\u7de8|Shinrin Hen}}\n# {{nihongo|The Giant Abobo Appears|\u5927\u7537\u30a2\u30dc\u30dc\u767b\u5834|\u014c Otoko Abobo T\u014dj\u014d}}\n# {{nihongo|The Hideout (Willy the Nemesis)|\u5927\u8981\u585e\uff08\u5bbf\u6575\u30a6\u30a3\u30ea\u30fc\uff09|Daiy\u014dsai (Shukuteki Uirii)}}\n# {{nihongo|Ending (Reunion with Marian)|\u30a8\u30f3\u30c7\u30a3\u30f3\u30b0\uff08\u30de\u30ea\u30a2\u30f3\u3068\u306e\u518d\u4f1a\uff09|Endingu (Marian to no Saikai)}}\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Final Fight]]''\n*''[[Gekido]]''\n*''[[Golden Axe]]''\n*''[[Kung-Fu Master (video game)|Kung-Fu Master]]''\n*[[Streets of Rage (series)|''Streets of Rage'' (series)]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{KLOV game|id=7619|name=Double Dragon}}\n*{{WoS game|id=0001456|name=Double Dragon}}\n*{{dmoz|Games/Video_Games/Fighting/Double_Dragon_Series/Double_Dragon|''Double Dragon''}}\n*[http://www.mobygames.com/game/double-dragon Double Dragon] at [[MobyGames]]\n*[http://www.hamster.co.jp/american_hamster/arcadearchives/doubledragon.htm Double Dragon [[Arcade Archives]] Page]\n*[http://doubledragon.kontek.net/games/dd/rddzeebo.html Zeebo Version Double Dragon Dojo Page]\n{{Double Dragon series}}\n\n[[Category:1987 video games]]\n[[Category:Amiga games]]\n[[Category:Amstrad CPC games]]\n[[Category:Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Arc System Works games]]\n[[Category:Atari 2600 games]]\n[[Category:Atari 7800 games]]\n[[Category:Atari Lynx games]]\n[[Category:Atari ST games]]\n[[Category:Beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Commodore 64 games]]\n[[Category:Cooperative video games]]\n[[Category:DOS games]]\n[[Category:Double Dragon]]\n[[Category:Game Boy Advance games]]\n[[Category:Game Boy games]]\n[[Category:Master System games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Entertainment System games]]\n[[Category:Sega Genesis games]]\n[[Category:Taito arcade games]]\n[[Category:Taito games]]\n[[Category:Techn\u014ds Japan beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Telegames games]]\n[[Category:Tiger handheld games]]\n[[Category:Tradewest games]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling beat 'em ups]]\n[[Category:Side-scrolling video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Japan]]\n[[Category:Video games scored by Barry Leitch]]\n[[Category:Video games with oblique graphics]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games]]\n[[Category:Virtual Console games for Wii U]]\n[[Category:Xbox 360 Live Arcade games]]\n[[Category:Zeebo games]]\n[[Category:ZX Spectrum games]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the 1987 video game release|the franchise|Double Dragon|other videogame topics|Double Dragon (disambiguation)}}\n{{More citations needed|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox video game\n|title = Double Dragon\n|image = Ddragon chirashi.jpg\n|caption = American promotional flyer for the arcade release by [[Taito]]. In this flyer, the main characters have their localized names as \"Hammer\" and \"Spike\".\n|developer = {{collapsible list|title=[[Techn\u014ds Japan]]|[[Arc System Works]] <small>(Master System)</small>}}\n|publisher = {{collapsible list|title=[[Taito Corporation|Taito]]<ref name=dd1_chirashi>{{cite web|url=http://www.flyerfever.com/post/92698052883/double-dragon|title=Double Dragon|website=Flyer Fever}}</ref>|[[Tradewest]] (NES) <br> [[Mastertronic]] (computers)<ref name=\"RetroGamer\">''[[Retro Gamer]]'', issue 1, p. 58, 2004</ref><br> [[Hamster Corporation|HAMSTER]] ([[PlayStation 4|PS4]])}}\n|director = [[Yoshihisa Kishimoto]]<br />Shinichi Saito\n|producer = Yoshihisa Kishimoto\n|designer = Koji Kai<br />Shinichi Saito\n|programmer = Hiroshi Satoh<br />Tomoyasu Koga<br />Nari Nishimura<br />Hideki Kaneda\n|composer = Kazunaka Yamane\n|artist = Kumiko Mukai<br />Mizuho Yama<br />Akemi Tasaki<br />Misae Nakaya<br />Masato Shiroto\n|release = July 10, [[1987 in video gaming|1987]] <ref name=\"CVG_ARC\"/>\n|genre = [[Beat 'em up]]\n|modes = Up to 2 players, simultaneous\n|platforms = {{collapsible list|title=[[Arcade game|Arcade]]|\n*[[Arcade game|Arcade]]\n*[[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]]\n*[[Master System]]\n*[[ZX Spectrum]]\n*[[Amstrad CPC]]\n*[[Commodore 64]]\n*[[IBM PC]]\n*[[Atari ST]]\n*[[Amiga]]\n*[[Atari 2600]]\n*[[Atari 7800]]\n*[[Game Boy]]\n*[[Game Boy Advance]] <small>(''Double Dragon advance'')</small>\n*[[Sega Genesis|Genesis]]\n*[[Atari Lynx|Lynx]]\n*[[Zeebo]]\n*[[Xbox 360]]\n*[[PlayStation 4]] ([[Arcade Archives]])\n*[[iOS]] <small>(''Trilogy'')</small>,<small>(''Double Dragon'')</small>\n*[[Android (operating system)|Android]] <small>(''Trilogy'')</small>,<small>(''Double Dragon'')</small>\n}}\n|series = ''[[Double Dragon]]''\n|cabinet = Upright\n|arcade system = Custom\n|cpu = '''Main'''\n*[[Hitachi 6309|HD6309]] @ [[Clock rate|12&nbsp;MHz]]\n\n'''Secondary'''\n*[[Hitachi 6309|HD63701]] @ 6&nbsp;[[Megahertz|MHz]]\n|sound = '''Sound CPU'''\n*[[Motorola 6809|M6809]] @ 1.5&nbsp;MHz\n'''[[Sound chip]]s'''\n*[[Yamaha YM2151|YM2151]] @ 3.579&nbsp;MHz\n*2\u00d7 MSM5205 @ 375&nbsp;[[Kilohertz|kHz]]\n|display = [[Raster graphics|Raster]] (Horizontal)\n\n'''Video'''\n*[[Display resolution|Resolution]]: 256\u00d7240 @ [[Refresh rate|57.44&nbsp;Hz]]\n*[[Color depth]]: [[List of monochrome and RGB palettes#12-bit RGB|12-bit]], 4096 colors\n*[[List of color palettes|On-screen colors]]: 384\n*On-screen [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]]: 64\n*[[Tile engine|Tiles]]: 16\u00d716 sprites, 16\u00d716 background, 8\u00d78 text\n*[[Tile engine|Tilemaps]]: 512\u00d7512 background, 256\u00d7256 text\n*[[Palette (computing)|Palettes]]: 16 colors (15 unique, 1 transparent) per tile, 8 dedicated tile palettes (3\u00d78\u00d716 = 384 colors)<ref>Information obtained from [http://mamedev.org MAME Source] (see [https://archive.is/20141207220921/https://github.com/mamedev/mame/blob/master/src/mame/drivers/ddragon.c Double Dragon])</ref>\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''''Double Dragon'''''|{{ruby|\u53cc\u622a\u9f8d|\u30c0\u30d6\u30eb\u30c9\u30e9\u30b4\u30f3}}|Daburu Doragon|lead=yes}}<ref>The kanji characters shown on the title screen are \u53cc\u622a\u9f8d, literally \"Twin (Measure-word) Dragons\". The characters on the title screen are as follows: shuang (double), jie (measure word for dragons, compare \"sheet\" for \"a sheet of paper\" or \"loaf\", \"a loaf of bread\"), long (dragon). This is an example of ''[[gikun]]'', in which characters are used to represent a meaning or ideal and not for phonetic value.</ref> is a 1987 [[beat 'em up]] [[video game]] developed by [[Techn\u014ds Japan]] and distributed in North America and Europe by [[Taito Corporation|Taito]]. The game is a spiritual and technological successor to Technos' earlier beat 'em up, ''Nekketsu K\u014dha Kunio-kun'' (released outside of Japan by Taito as ''[[Renegade (video game)|Renegade]]''), but introduced several additions such as two-player [[cooperative gameplay]] and the ability to arm oneself with an enemy's weapon after disarming them. ''Double Dragon'' is considered to be one of the first successful examples of the genre, resulting in the creation of two arcade sequels and several spinoffs, as well as inspiring other companies in creating their own beat 'em ups.\n\nOriginally an [[arcade game]], home versions were released for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]], [[Master System]], [[Atari 2600]], [[Atari 7800]], [[Atari ST]], [[Amiga]], [[Amstrad CPC]], [[Commodore 64]], [[Game Boy]], [[Sega Mega Drive|Genesis/Mega Drive]] and [[Atari Lynx]], among other platforms during the series's height of popularity. A [[video game remake|remake]] titled ''[[Double Dragon Advance]]'' was released for the [[Game Boy Advance]] in 2003.\n\n==Arcade version==\n[[File:DDArcade.png|thumb|left|Billy and Jimmy face off against Jick, the boss at the end of the first stage (arcade version)]]\n\nThe player takes control of martial artist Billy Lee, or his twin brother Jimmy (also known as Hammer and Spike in the supplementary materials for the American arcade release), as they fight their way into the turf of the Black Warriors gang in order to rescue Billy's love interest, Marian. The player character has a repertoire of martial arts techniques which they can perform by using the joystick and three action buttons (kick, jump, and punch) individually or in combination. Techniques range from basic punches and kicks to more elaborate attacks such as throws and elbow strikes. When playing with another player, one can grab an opponent from behind, allowing the other to attack unimpeded. Caution should be taken, though, as some enemies are able to do the same thing to the players. The player begins the game with a certain number of extra lives and a life gauge which depletes as the player takes hits, and must complete each stage within a time limit. One life is lost if either the life gauge or timer reaches zero, or if the player character falls off the bottom of the screen or into a hole, river, or bed of spikes.\n\nCertain enemies carry melee weapons, which can be knocked out of their hands and picked up to use against them. Available weapons include baseball bats, whips, throwing knives, and dynamite; in addition, rocks, oil drums, and boxes can be found in certain places.\n\nThe players encounter seven different types of enemies during the game; with the exception of Linda and Willy, all have two different skin colors.\n\n* '''Williams:''' A low-ranking member of the gang, who can use bats, knives, and dynamite.\n* '''Rowper:''' Another low-ranking member, who can use the same weapons as Williams and also throws rocks, oil drums, and boxes.\n* '''Linda:''' The only female member, and the only one who will pick up or carry a whip; she uses no other weapon.\n* '''Abobo:''' A tall, bald, shirtless gang member who can throw heavy items.\n* '''Jick:'''<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://twitter.com/chou_nosuke/status/712640167777931264|magazine=Famicom Ts\u016bshin|title=\u30d3\u30c7\u30f2\u30b2\u30fc\u30e0\u901a\u4fe123|trans-title=Video Arcade Journal 23|date=May 29, 1987|author=Tajiri Satoshi|authorlink=Satoshi Tajiri|pages=88\u201390}}</ref> The boss of the first stage, identical in appearance to Abobo except for the addition of a beard, sunglasses, and a Mohawk hairstyle.\n* '''Jeff:''' The boss of the second stage, who is a head swap of the Lee brothers.\n* '''Willy:''' The leader of the gang, and the final boss. He carries a machine gun whose bullets can instantly kill Billy and Jimmy, and he never drops it when knocked down.\n\nThe game is divided into four different stages or \"missions,\" which consist of a city slum, a factory, a forest, and the gang's hideout. The game normally ends if a single player defeats the final boss alone. However, if two players manage to complete the game together, they are then forced to fight each other in order to determine who will win Marian's affections. Both life gauges are refilled, any extra lives are taken away, and the timer is reset for this fight.\n\nThe original arcade version displayed 384 colors on the screen, out of a 4096 ([[List of monochrome and RGB palettes#12-bit RGB|12-bit]]) [[List of color palettes|color palette]]. The hardware used several [[8-bit]] [[microprocessor]]s running in parallel; [[16-bit]] processors were expensive at the time the game was first released. Along with the multiple [[Hitachi 6309|Hitachi HD6309]] based processors, multiple processors were dedicated to sound, such as the [[Yamaha YM2151]] [[frequency modulation synthesis|FM synthesis]] [[sound chip]].\n\n==Home versions==\n===Famicom/NES===\n[[File:Double Dragon NES Screenshot.png|thumb|The first fight scene in the NES version of the game]]\n\n''Double Dragon'' was ported to the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Family Computer]] by Techn\u014ds Japan in 1988. The game was published for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] in North America by [[Tradewest]], who was given the license to produce other home versions of the game as well, and by [[Nintendo]] in Europe. The NES version of ''Double Dragon'' was released for the [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] service on April 25, 2008, in Europe and on April 28, 2008, in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.uk/Games/NES/Double-Dragon-838908.html|title=Double Dragon|website=Nintendo of Europe GmbH|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/|title=Nintendo - Official Site - Video Game Consoles, Games|website=www.nintendo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> It was also released in North America on December 12, 2013, for the Nintendo 3DS and the Wii U although in Europe, the former was released on December 5, 2013, while the latter was released on March 13, 2014.<ref>{{cite news|title=Double Dragon Now Available on Wii Shop Channel!|url=https://www.nintendo.com/whatsnew/detail/L9y02rqdU9RwqNZ2FeZ2xsmO53OpLc4B|publisher=Nintendo of America|date=2008-04-28|accessdate=2008-05-01}}</ref><ref>https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/double-dragon-nes-3ds</ref><ref>https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/3P5rmneYKSyMkMz4xp_oo9NIatLqth-p</ref>\n\nThe most notable difference the NES version has from the arcade game is the omission of the arcade's two players cooperative game mode in favor of alternating play. The plot was altered as a result of this change - instead of having both Lee brothers as protagonists, the NES version has players controlling Billy Lee as the lone protagonist, with Jimmy Lee serving as the antagonist and true leader of the Black Warriors.\n\nDue to technical limitations of the NES that were not worked around, the game can only generate two enemies on-screen to confront the player and both enemies are the same character. Additionally, all weapons on the screen (including any carried by the player) disappear once a group of enemies has been defeated. A level-up system was also implemented. The player begins the game with only the basic punches and kicks available to their character, gaining the most powerful ones after acquiring the experience points needed to use them. The player has a total of seven skill levels that they can achieve throughout the game.\n\nThe level designs are very different, with some stages featuring new areas (notably the cavern section in Mission 3) that feature greater emphasis on jumping over platforms or evading traps. Most of the enemies from the arcade version also appear, with the exception of Jick and Jeff. A new enemy character, a Chinese martial arts master named Chin Taimei (shortened to Chintai in the localized version) serves as the boss of the second stage and appears as a recurring minor enemy for the rest of the game.\n\n====Mode B====\nThe NES version features a bonus game mode (dubbed \"Mode B\") where the player can choose between Billy or one of five enemy characters (Will, Rowper, Linda, Chin, and Abobo) from the main game and compete against a [[palette swap|double]] of their character controlled by the computer or a second player in a one-on-one match. Matches against the computer are handicapped in favor of the computer-controlled character, while certain characters will get a chance to wield a weapon in the 2-Players matches. The mode features larger sprites different from the main game itself.\n\n''Double Dragon'' was only the second game that Techn\u014ds developed for the NES, and the two-player mode was reputedly omitted because of the programmers' inexperience with the hardware. This also accounts for the game's large number of bugs and glitches. Also, the \"Mode B\" was said to be a prototype originally planned for the main game.\n\n===Master System===\nShortly after the release of the NES version, [[Sega]] acquired the rights to develop its own port of the game for the Sega Mark III and [[Sega Master System|Master System]] with the Master System version being developed by [[Arc System Works]] (who would eventually gain the rights for the franchise as part of their Intellectual Property portfolio). The game supports the optional FM Sound Unit sold separately for the Mark III and which is already integrated into the Japanese Master System models.\n\nThis version featured brighter colors and displaying up to three different enemies on-screen, although weapons are limited to only one per screen. The game retains the two-player co-op mode (including the final face off between both players) and has level designs that were closer to the arcade game (aside from missing ladders in some areas). This version retains the Mission 2 end-boss, a head swap of the Lee brothers (who is given the name Jeff in this version). However, the mohawk version of Abobo is missing in this version as well, being replaced by black and green [[palette swap]]s of the bald Abobo as stage bosses.\n\nThe Master System version allows for unlimited continues until the final stage. However, if a player performs a number of 10 backward jump kicks at the start of the final stage, they retain their unlimited continues.\n\n===Game Boy===\nIn [[1990 in video gaming|1990]], Techn\u014ds Japan produced a [[Game Boy]] version of ''Double Dragon'', which was also released in North America and Europe by Tradewest. This version features gameplay similar to the NES version, but with completely different level designs and all of the main character's moves available from the start. The enemies are the same as the NES version, but some of the characters such as Abobo and Chin were given new techniques. The main game mode is still single player, although the game ends after the fight with Willy, with Jimmy not appearing in the main game. A two-player Versus Mode is also included like in the NES version, but the only characters available to play as are the Lee brothers. This version has also been re-released on the [[Virtual Console]] for the Nintendo 3DS in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.com/games/detail/double-dragon-gb-3ds/|title=Double Dragon for Nintendo 3DS - Nintendo Game Details|website=www.nintendo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n===Home computers===\nVersions of ''Double Dragon'' have been produced for various other platforms as well. In [[1988 in video gaming|1988]], [[Activision]] released versions of ''Double Dragon'' for the [[Atari 2600]] and [[Atari 7800]]. In addition, home computer versions of the game were released for the [[Amiga]], [[Atari ST]], [[Commodore 64]], [[ZX Spectrum]], [[Amstrad CPC]], and [[PC compatible]]s. Most were developed by UK-based Binary Designs aside from the PC port, which was developed by Arcadia Software.\n\nTwo different Amstrad CPC versions were produced: one was released for the CPC6128 (128&nbsp;kB RAM) based on the Amiga version, while the other was released for the CPC464 (tape and 64&nbsp;kB RAM) and was ported from the Sinclair version. In [[1991 in video gaming|1991]], a second Commodore 64 version was released by Ocean Software unrelated to the earlier Binary Designs port. It came on a special 32k bank-switched cartridge and did not support two-player mode.\n\nThe original Binary Designs port of ''Double Dragon'' for the Commodore 64 was heavily criticized for its poor quality and is often considered one of the worst commercially-released C64 games and one of the worst arcade conversions of all time. The game was reportedly done by extremely inexperienced programmers on a very tight deadline<ref>https://www.lemon64.com/?mainurl=https%3A//www.lemon64.com/games/details.php%3FID%3D752</ref> and lacked almost all of the gameplay elements of the arcade game. Only two weapons (the whip and baseball bat) are available and backgrounds are static; the player cannot climb or jump on or interact with them, and the battle with the final boss at the end is absent. The game also featured a visible gap between the characters' upper and lower bodies due to a poorly coded sprite multiplexer routine; the instruction manual included an apology message from the programming team for this visual artifact.\n\n===Other platforms===\nIn [[1992 in video gaming|1992]], [[Accolade (company)|Accolade]] released a [[Sega Genesis|Mega Drive/Genesis]] port of the game in North America and Europe under the Ballistic Software label. This version was released as an unlicensed third-party cartridge. Although the Mega Drive/Genesis has a smaller color palette than the arcade original, due to the more powerful 16-bit hardware it actually fixes all of the slow down problems from the original arcade game. However, it had a number of deficiencies (especially in sound quality) because Ballistic Software were forced to use a small 512k (4 Meg) cartridge ROM for cost reasons. This version came closest to the arcade game at the time.\n\nAn [[Atari Lynx]] version was released in [[1993 in video gaming|1993]], developed by Knight Technologies and published by [[Telegames]].\n\nIn [[2003 in video gaming|2003]], a remake of the original arcade game titled ''[[Double Dragon Advance]]'' was released for the [[Game Boy Advance]]. This version features four additional stages interspersed between the four original stages, as a new set of moves and enemy characters, some of which are lifted or inspired by other games in the series. It was published by [[Atlus]] under license from Million Corporation, the company which held the IP to the series at the time. In [[2006 in video gaming|2006]], a [[Mobile gaming|mobile phone game]] based on ''Double Dragon Advance'' was released titled ''Double Dragon EX''. It was developed by [[South Korea|Korean]]-based [[Eolith (company)|Eolith]].\n\nAn [[Xbox Live Arcade]] version of ''Double Dragon'' was released on May 9, for the [[Xbox 360]] in [[2007 in video gaming|2007]]. This version features an emulation of the original arcade game, as well as an optional game mode featuring redrawn high definition graphics and a remixed soundtrack. It also features support for online multiplayer. It was delisted on July 1, 2009, due to the closure of its publisher, [[Empire Interactive]].\n\n[[2011 in video gaming|2011]] saw the release of a new version of ''Double Dragon'' for [[iOS]] and [[Android (OS)|Android]] devices. It was again developed by Brizo Interactive under license from Million, in collaboration with [[Aksys Games]], and published by Bow Mobile Corp. It employs brand new artwork and sprites, Bluetooth multiplayer connectivity, online score ranking, and a host of other new and unique features, new to the franchise.\n\nThe arcade version of ''Double Dragon'' was re-released in [[2013 in video gaming|2013]] alongside its two sequels in a compilation titled ''Double Dragon Trilogy'' produced by [[DotEmu]], which was released on [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], and [[Steam (software)|Steam]] platforms.\n\n==Reception==\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" style=\"float:right; font-size:80%; text-align:center; margin:1em; margin-top:0; padding:0; background:none;\" cellpadding=\"0\"\n! colspan=12 style=\"font-size: 120%\" | Reception\n|-\n! colspan=12 | [[Video game journalism|Reviews]]\n|-\n! rowspan=2 | Publication\n! colspan=11 | Score\n|-\n! [[Arcade game|ARC]]\n! [[Master System|SMS]]\n! [[Sega Mega Drive|MD/GEN]]\n! [[Sega Game Gear|GG]]\n! [[Nintendo Entertainment System|NES]]\n! [[Game Boy|GB]]\n! [[Commodore 64|C64]]\n! [[Amiga|AMI]]\n! [[Atari ST|ST]]\n! [[ZX Spectrum|ZX]]\n|-\n| ''[[ACE (games magazine)|ACE]]''\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| 863<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_37667 |title=Double Dragon review from ACE: Advanced Computer Entertainment 37 (Oct 1990) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| 298<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_37852 |title=Double Dragon review from ACE: Advanced Computer Entertainment 21 (Jun 1989) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| 275<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_37851 |title=Double Dragon review from ACE: Advanced Computer Entertainment 21 (Jun 1989) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n|-\n| ''[[Commodore User]]''\n| 9/10<ref name=\"CU_ARC\">{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_12482 |title=Double Dragon review from Commodore User (Aug 1987) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessdate=2015-09-05}}</ref>\n| \n| \n| \n| \n| \n| 43%<ref>{{cite web|url=http://amr.abime.net/review_14491 |title=Double Dragon review from Commodore User (Jan 1989) - Amiga Magazine Rack |publisher=Amr.abime.net |date= |accessd